1
00:00:36,080 --> 00:00:38,548
[Sweeping instrumental music]

2
00:01:44,760 --> 00:01:47,513
But, Father Fitzgibbon,
why do you want a new furnace?

3
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:51,752
Because, Mr. Haines, last winter,
in the month of November alone...

4
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:54,479
four of me parishioners
took to the bed with pneumonia.

5
00:01:54,560 --> 00:01:55,675
That's too bad.

6
00:01:55,760 --> 00:01:58,513
It's only by a miracle
that I meself pulled through.

7
00:01:58,920 --> 00:02:02,390
It'll only cost $632.50...

8
00:02:02,480 --> 00:02:04,277
complete with an automatic damper.

9
00:02:04,360 --> 00:02:07,318
But, Father, I didn't come here
to put in new furnaces.

10
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:09,470
I think you ought to give him
his furnace, Dad.

11
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:12,996
It would warm people's hearts,
and maybe his collections would be bigger.

12
00:02:13,080 --> 00:02:16,390
No, Son. Improvements are out.
Now, Father...

13
00:02:16,480 --> 00:02:18,550
That was good.
What he said, that was good.

14
00:02:18,640 --> 00:02:21,279
Well, he's new to our business.
Now, Father...

15
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:23,430
- No furnace?
- No furnace.

16
00:02:23,520 --> 00:02:25,238
Now, Father, here's my business.

17
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:28,153
You owe the Knickerbocker Savings
and Loan Company...

18
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:31,198
five payments on this mortgage.
If they're not taken care of...

19
00:02:31,280 --> 00:02:33,953
I'm afraid the Knickerbocker Savings
and Loan Company...

20
00:02:34,040 --> 00:02:36,634
will have to take the necessary action.

21
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:39,553
Why don't you make it
the subject of your sermon next Sunday?

22
00:02:39,640 --> 00:02:42,552
Tell it to your people.
"The Lord loveth a cheerful giver."

23
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:46,189
Oh, I can imagine meself
saying that in Mass next Sunday.

24
00:02:46,320 --> 00:02:48,834
What a sermon that would be, Mr. Haines.

25
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:51,309
<i>"The text of me sermon this morning...</i>

26
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:54,153
"is taken from the mortgage...

27
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:56,870
"according to Mr. Haines...

28
00:02:57,360 --> 00:03:00,238
"from the <i>1</i>st to the 23rd clause."

29
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:06,793
- Very dull, you know.
- But that's your business. Keep it bright.

30
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,072
But seriously, Father,
we've made a bad loan...

31
00:03:10,680 --> 00:03:12,511
and we want our money back.

32
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:16,673
- Well, you'll get it somehow.
- That's all I wanted to know.

33
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:19,229
Good day, Father. Come on, Son.

34
00:03:31,160 --> 00:03:32,513
Dad.

35
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:37,718
You can't foreclose.
Why, it just isn't being done.

36
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:40,951
I read up on it. There's never been
a Catholic church foreclosure...

37
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:45,158
- in the history of New York.
- There's always a first time, isn't there?

38
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:47,840
Don't you think you're being
a little harsh with him?

39
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:51,913
You've got to be.
Son, never loan money to a church.

40
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:56,119
As soon as you start to close in on them,
everybody thinks you're a heel.

41
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:01,789
- Well, aren't you?
- Yes.

42
00:04:06,160 --> 00:04:10,119
Good morning. Could you tell me
where I'd find Saint Dominic's Church?

43
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:11,428
[Exclaims questioningly]

44
00:04:11,520 --> 00:04:14,353
O'MALLEY: I'm looking
for St. Dominic's Church.

45
00:04:14,440 --> 00:04:15,475
Why?

46
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:20,596
- I'm gonna work there.
- The new assistant?

47
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:25,240
And you can't even find the church.

48
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:30,872
<i>Well, all I can say is, young man,</i>
<i>you're off to a mighty bad start.</i>

49
00:04:31,720 --> 00:04:32,994
What's your name?

50
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:36,470
Father O'Malley.
Charles Francis Patrick O'Malley.

51
00:04:36,920 --> 00:04:39,354
O'MALLEY: What's yours?
WOMAN: Her name is Quimp!

52
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:42,348
Hattie Quimp!

53
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:44,112
You'll see a lot of her, you will.

54
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:47,112
At St. Dominic's,
she's a regular two-a-dayer.

55
00:04:47,240 --> 00:04:49,959
Very religious, burns candles.

56
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:52,919
I could tell you plenty about them, too.

57
00:04:53,720 --> 00:04:57,076
And if I did, they'd have
to leave the neighbourhood.

58
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:04,519
If you're looking for St. Dominic's, Father,
it's a block up and then to your left.

59
00:05:04,600 --> 00:05:05,953
Thank you.

60
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:19,758
- Hello.
- Hello.

61
00:05:19,840 --> 00:05:23,628
- How's things going?
- Terrible. They never hit one to me.

62
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:27,233
Watch right field for me a minute,
will you, Father?

63
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:29,117
- Sure.
- I got to run in the house.

64
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:30,269
O'MALLEY: Okay.

65
00:05:30,360 --> 00:05:33,636
BOY <i>1</i>: Hey, fellas,
the Father's gonna take my place.

66
00:05:34,160 --> 00:05:35,593
BOY 2: Okay, Father.

67
00:05:38,360 --> 00:05:40,032
O'MALLEY: I got it! Got it!

68
00:05:42,520 --> 00:05:44,431
BOYS: Hurry up! Come on!

69
00:05:46,440 --> 00:05:47,634
Thanks.

70
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:58,429
- What do you think you're doing?
- I'm the substitute right fielder.

71
00:05:58,520 --> 00:06:00,272
You ought to be ashamed of yourself...

72
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:02,920
playing around with kids,
smashing people's windows.

73
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,639
MAN: A big grown-up man.
HATTIE: And a priest, besides.

74
00:06:05,720 --> 00:06:09,269
- Hello.
- Still looking for St. Dominic's.

75
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,355
You just wait till I tell Father Fitzgibbon.

76
00:06:12,440 --> 00:06:14,749
Look, you keep out of this, will you? Go on.

77
00:06:14,840 --> 00:06:16,512
This is between him and me.

78
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:18,830
O'MALLEY: Honestly, I'm sorry
about the window.

79
00:06:18,920 --> 00:06:20,956
Yeah, but being sorry don't fix it.

80
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:22,871
O'MALLEY: I intend to pay for it.
MAN: When?

81
00:06:22,960 --> 00:06:24,518
Priests never have any money.

82
00:06:24,600 --> 00:06:27,034
- That window...
- Now wait a minute, my good man...

83
00:06:27,160 --> 00:06:29,754
I said I'd pay for it. I told you I'm sorry.

84
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:33,155
What else can I say after I say I'm sorry?

85
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:35,595
That ain't the idea.
It's the principle of the thing.

86
00:06:35,680 --> 00:06:38,148
A priest shouldn't go around
breaking people's windows.

87
00:06:38,240 --> 00:06:39,912
It sets a bad example for the children.

88
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,788
You got me stymied there. I'm contrite
and I'm penitent. I've told you I'm sorry.

89
00:06:43,880 --> 00:06:48,431
- You told me that twice. But that don't...
- That doesn't fix the broken window, I know.

90
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:51,188
I think you're just playing hard
to get along with.

91
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:53,794
Maybe a little security might help?

92
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:56,751
These were given to me.

93
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,152
Why don't you keep them until I've made
good? Maybe they'll make you feel better.

94
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:04,629
They're mother of pearl, you see?

95
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:07,393
If that'll satisfy you, I'll run along.

96
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,834
Hey, you, here, I got no use for this.
First place, I don't believe in it.

97
00:07:13,920 --> 00:07:16,070
As a matter of fact,
I don't believe in anything.

98
00:07:16,160 --> 00:07:19,470
- I can believe that.
- I'm an atheist. Besides, I'm superstitious.

99
00:07:19,560 --> 00:07:22,632
All right, then, I'm sorry about the window.
I'll have it fixed.

100
00:07:22,720 --> 00:07:24,711
Can I have the ball back?

101
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,275
You even throw like an atheist.

102
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:04,798
Mrs. Carmody,
did the young priest come yet?

103
00:08:05,040 --> 00:08:08,828
He's here, but he insisted on
changing his clothes before seeing you.

104
00:08:08,920 --> 00:08:11,434
That's nice. Tidy himself up a bit.

105
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:15,678
Hello, Father.

106
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:22,470
I'm your new curate, Father.

107
00:08:22,560 --> 00:08:24,869
<i>If you'll excuse my appearance.</i>

108
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:30,155
No, it's not possible.
The Bishop may have a grudge against me.

109
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:33,392
He may think I've a mouthful of clover
and can't preach...

110
00:08:33,480 --> 00:08:37,029
but even the Bishop
wouldn't do a thing like this to me.

111
00:08:39,040 --> 00:08:40,837
I see what you mean.

112
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:46,789
Young man, may I ask...

113
00:08:46,880 --> 00:08:49,952
is that the official garb
of the priests in St. Louis?

114
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:53,392
No, I...
Something happened to me on the way over.

115
00:08:54,520 --> 00:08:57,159
I guess this just isn't my day, Father.

116
00:08:57,240 --> 00:08:59,276
- Do you mind if I...
- No.

117
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:06,956
[Exclaims admonishingly]

118
00:09:13,680 --> 00:09:16,353
Young man, as a matter of curiosity...

119
00:09:17,160 --> 00:09:19,390
what made you become a priest?

120
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:22,268
Why, l...

121
00:09:22,360 --> 00:09:24,032
[Telephone rings]

122
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:28,394
Hello?

123
00:09:30,160 --> 00:09:31,957
Well, you don't say.

124
00:09:34,560 --> 00:09:36,471
You don't say.

125
00:09:37,920 --> 00:09:40,639
<i>Oh, yes, I can well believe it, yeah.</i>

126
00:09:40,720 --> 00:09:42,119
Mrs. Quimp?

127
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:49,838
[Clears throat]

128
00:09:50,280 --> 00:09:52,191
Yes, indeed, Mrs. Quimp.

129
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,352
I appreciate your good intentions.
Yes. Goodbye.

130
00:09:56,960 --> 00:10:00,714
- I guess she told you about me?
- Yeah, the garrulous old biddy.

131
00:10:01,600 --> 00:10:04,160
Young man, I'm afraid
you're off to a very bad start.

132
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:07,357
That's what she said. I'm sorry, Father, I...

133
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:10,238
Smashing people's windows. Such conduct.

134
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:14,154
Oh, yes, that reminds me.
I wanted to ask you something.

135
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:19,511
Listen now. Tell me, young man,
how did you happen to become a priest?

136
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:21,439
[Laughing] Well, l...

137
00:10:21,520 --> 00:10:23,238
[Telephone rings]

138
00:10:25,440 --> 00:10:26,555
Yeah.

139
00:10:28,080 --> 00:10:29,718
Chuck? Chuck who?

140
00:10:31,640 --> 00:10:33,631
- Father Chuck?
- That's me.

141
00:10:34,680 --> 00:10:36,875
Here, I'll take it over here.

142
00:10:39,320 --> 00:10:41,788
Hello? Timmy!

143
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:45,552
Well, how are you, Timmy? I just got in.

144
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:47,998
Well, what do you know?

145
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:51,789
That's Father O'Dowd, an old friend of mine.
We used to go to school together.

146
00:10:51,880 --> 00:10:55,589
[Singing] <i>Hail Alma Mater</i>
<i>Thy time-honoured halls</i>

147
00:10:55,880 --> 00:10:59,668
<i>Shall echo with our praise till we die</i>

148
00:10:59,800 --> 00:11:04,237
<i>And 'round our hearts</i>
<i>are the ivy-covered walls</i>

149
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:07,989
<i>Of East St. Louis</i>

150
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:09,308
<i>High</i>

151
00:11:09,400 --> 00:11:13,393
Good, Chuck. Can't you talk?

152
00:11:13,480 --> 00:11:14,629
[Humming hesitantly]

153
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:15,948
Well, no.

154
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:20,312
All right, then, I'll do the talking.
How does your new pastor impress you?

155
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:24,551
You're a big help. It's a little early to say.

156
00:11:25,640 --> 00:11:27,437
Time will tell, though.

157
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:29,233
[Exclaims negatively]

158
00:11:29,320 --> 00:11:33,108
No, I think it would be better
if I told you when I saw you.

159
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:35,710
Yes, it would be much better.

160
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,037
All right, Timmy, make it soon, huh?
So long.

161
00:11:39,880 --> 00:11:42,440
- He's a great little man.
- Yeah.

162
00:11:43,880 --> 00:11:47,077
What were we talking about?
Yes, I was going to ask...

163
00:11:47,200 --> 00:11:49,589
You were going to ask me
if I want to see the church.

164
00:11:49,680 --> 00:11:51,591
- Yes, that's right.
- Yes.

165
00:12:04,480 --> 00:12:06,516
[Church bell chiming]

166
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:18,153
- I like this. It's beautiful.
- Thank you.

167
00:12:18,240 --> 00:12:21,710
- How long you been here, Father?
- Forty-five years.

168
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:23,752
- And the...
- Forty-six in October.

169
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:27,037
- The church?
- Same. I built it.

170
00:12:27,560 --> 00:12:30,791
I can only hope someday I can say
I built as much.

171
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:36,673
- This is nice.
- Yeah, the birds like it.

172
00:12:37,640 --> 00:12:40,074
They're good company. Listen.

173
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:43,191
[Lmitates bird chirping]

174
00:12:44,920 --> 00:12:46,194
[O'Malley clears throat]

175
00:12:46,280 --> 00:12:48,635
I've taken a great deal of pleasure
in me garden.

176
00:12:48,720 --> 00:12:51,075
It's been hard work, but it's been worth it.

177
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:55,638
I think you'll find this a very pleasant place
in which to meditate.

178
00:12:56,800 --> 00:13:00,793
- You do meditate, don't you?
- Oh, yes, sure.

179
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:03,391
FITZGIBBON: Now I'll show you the church.

180
00:13:03,480 --> 00:13:06,313
FITZGIBBON: What we really need
is a loudspeaker system.

181
00:13:13,560 --> 00:13:17,473
For a minute I thought I found
a four-leaf clover. Guess it just isn't my day.

182
00:13:17,560 --> 00:13:18,993
Would you like to see the church?

183
00:13:19,080 --> 00:13:20,308
O'MALLEY: Yes.

184
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:35,989
[Organ playing]

185
00:14:04,520 --> 00:14:06,988
[Organ playing continues]

186
00:14:28,640 --> 00:14:31,029
Mrs. Carmody, just a minute.

187
00:14:32,040 --> 00:14:33,519
Just a minute.

188
00:14:33,760 --> 00:14:37,435
FITZGIBBON: Where's Father O'Malley?
MRS. CARMODY: He left early this morning.

189
00:14:37,720 --> 00:14:40,871
The young man doesn't sleep
as late as you do, you know.

190
00:14:41,640 --> 00:14:44,518
- What's this?
- His luggage. It just arrived.

191
00:14:44,680 --> 00:14:48,559
Golf, tennis. And where, may I ask,
is his fish pole?

192
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:50,039
It's here.

193
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:51,873
[Harrumphs]

194
00:15:00,880 --> 00:15:03,553
- Good morning, Father.
- Been to market?

195
00:15:03,640 --> 00:15:07,269
Mrs. Carmody could attend to that.
You should have been making parish calls.

196
00:15:07,360 --> 00:15:11,148
I have. Mrs. McGonigle, the one
with the big house and rheumatism.

197
00:15:11,240 --> 00:15:13,356
- She sent you a present.
- She did?

198
00:15:13,440 --> 00:15:17,911
Very generous of her, I must say.
A fine Christian woman, Mrs. McGonigle.

199
00:15:18,880 --> 00:15:21,235
Wonder what it is.
Something to eat, I dare say.

200
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:24,517
Jam. No, pickled pig's feet.

201
00:15:25,320 --> 00:15:27,914
Possibly some brandied peaches.

202
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:32,192
If there's one thing I'm partial to,
it's a nice big jar of brandied peaches.

203
00:15:32,280 --> 00:15:35,556
- A nice basket, too.
- Yes. She wants it back.

204
00:15:37,800 --> 00:15:39,791
[Puppies whimpering]

205
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:44,517
They're too young. Much too young
to be separated from their mother.

206
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:47,478
That's what she said. So here's the mother.

207
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:51,229
- Isn't she cute?
- The joy of giving is indeed a pleasure.

208
00:15:51,320 --> 00:15:53,880
Especially when you get rid
of something you don't want.

209
00:15:53,960 --> 00:15:56,554
Mrs. McGonigle is famous for these tricks.

210
00:15:56,640 --> 00:16:00,599
When her husband died,
she sent me his umbrella...

211
00:16:00,680 --> 00:16:04,514
his long flannel underwear,
and his moustache cup.

212
00:16:06,920 --> 00:16:10,230
[Singing] <i>Hail Alma Mater</i>
<i>Thy time-honoured halls</i>

213
00:16:10,320 --> 00:16:13,153
<i>Shall echo with our praise till we die</i>

214
00:16:13,240 --> 00:16:16,471
<i>And 'round our hearts</i>
<i>are the ivy-covered walls</i>

215
00:16:16,560 --> 00:16:20,109
<i>Of East St. Louis High</i>

216
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:23,437
O'MALLEY: Timmy, how are you?
O'DOWD: Chuck, I'm glad to see you.

217
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:25,158
O'DOWD: How long
since we've seen each other?

218
00:16:25,240 --> 00:16:26,309
O'MALLEY: Four years.

219
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:28,470
- Five, anyway.
- Has it been that long?

220
00:16:28,560 --> 00:16:31,791
Pardon me. Father Fitzgibbon,
this is my old friend, Father O'Dowd.

221
00:16:31,880 --> 00:16:33,199
How are you, Father Fitzgibbon?

222
00:16:33,280 --> 00:16:35,840
We've been friends
since we were knee-high to a niblick.

223
00:16:35,920 --> 00:16:38,115
<i>He was our local Huckleberry Finn.</i>

224
00:16:38,200 --> 00:16:40,316
"Laugh and the world laughs with you,"
he'd say.

225
00:16:40,400 --> 00:16:41,913
Cry, and you cry all by yourself.

226
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,149
How are you, Father?

227
00:16:43,240 --> 00:16:47,518
I just dropped by to see if Father O'Malley
could play a little golf this afternoon.

228
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:52,116
- You did? Where's your parish?
- Right over here, St. Francis.

229
00:16:53,360 --> 00:16:57,239
Well, now, about your golf.
Of course, I can't answer for you...

230
00:16:57,320 --> 00:17:01,950
but at St. Dominic's we've very little time
for games of golf and such like.

231
00:17:02,320 --> 00:17:06,632
If you were working for me, all I can say
is that you wouldn't have time for it, either.

232
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:09,871
It's lucky for me then that I'm at St. Francis.

233
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:15,273
It's my hope St. Francis can say the same.

234
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:18,194
- He's got you there, Timmy.
- Good, Father, very good.

235
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:20,919
Father, why don't you come with us?
It's a grand game.

236
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:23,673
Sure, we'll teach you.
A man is never too old to learn.

237
00:17:23,760 --> 00:17:27,514
O'DOWD: Lot of fresh air on the golf course.
O'MALLEY: And profanity, too.

238
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:31,593
No, a golf course is nothing
but a poolroom moved outdoors.

239
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,878
You mind if I use that one sometime,
Father?

240
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:39,350
Young man, would you mind...

241
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:44,514
- How did he ever become a priest?
- Well, I don't...

242
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:49,758
- Father Fitzgibbon.
- Excuse me.

243
00:17:53,400 --> 00:17:55,356
FITZGIBBON: Who is it?
MRS. CARMODY: Mrs. Quimp.

244
00:17:55,440 --> 00:17:56,759
[Mumbling]

245
00:17:59,400 --> 00:18:01,356
- Does he know?
- Does he know what?

246
00:18:01,440 --> 00:18:04,398
- That you're in charge.
- How'd you know?

247
00:18:04,480 --> 00:18:08,109
I didn't. I gathered as much
when I heard you were here.

248
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:11,476
Everybody knows
that St. Dominic's is in a bad way.

249
00:18:11,560 --> 00:18:13,994
Father Fitzgibbon
is getting to be an old man.

250
00:18:14,080 --> 00:18:16,389
- This needs a young fellow...
- Timmy, look.

251
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:18,516
- Don't mention it to anybody.
- No.

252
00:18:18,600 --> 00:18:21,558
When I had my talk with the Bishop,
it was our understanding...

253
00:18:21,640 --> 00:18:24,234
that Father Fitzgibbon
was to remain here as pastor...

254
00:18:24,320 --> 00:18:28,074
and I was to try and straighten out
St. Dominic's without hurting his feelings.

255
00:18:28,160 --> 00:18:32,836
I see. You're in charge, but you're not.
I don't think I'd like an assignment like that.

256
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:37,238
But the Bishop couldn't very well
put him out to pasture, could he?

257
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:42,156
"Pasture"?
What's this I hear about a pasture?

258
00:18:44,480 --> 00:18:46,550
I was just saying to him, Father...

259
00:18:46,640 --> 00:18:50,679
the next time I come past your church
I'm going to drop in and see you.

260
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:53,194
Good day, Father. So long, Chuck.

261
00:18:54,840 --> 00:18:56,034
[O'Malley clears throat]

262
00:18:56,120 --> 00:18:59,999
I was going to ask you something.
Oh, yes, the telephone.

263
00:19:00,840 --> 00:19:03,957
Mrs. Quimp just telephoned.
Her landlord is throwing her out again.

264
00:19:04,040 --> 00:19:06,349
She wants somebody to go and see her.
You better go.

265
00:19:06,440 --> 00:19:09,955
I'll go right along, Father.
Would you mind the puppies?

266
00:19:15,280 --> 00:19:16,633
Thank you.

267
00:19:17,640 --> 00:19:19,710
I'll bet you're the new assistant...

268
00:19:19,800 --> 00:19:22,872
the one who's going to get St. Dominic's
out of all its trouble.

269
00:19:22,960 --> 00:19:26,839
And I'll bet you're all the trouble.
I'll wager you're the man with the mortgage.

270
00:19:26,920 --> 00:19:29,878
- You've heard about the mortgage?
- All churches have mortgages.

271
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:32,190
It isn't respectable
for a church not to have one.

272
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:33,998
- My name's O'Malley.
- Mine's Haines.

273
00:19:34,080 --> 00:19:37,789
Nice meeting you. We may have to
touch you for a little more a little later on.

274
00:19:37,880 --> 00:19:40,030
We're gonna need
a new paint job here soon.

275
00:19:40,120 --> 00:19:44,272
I must run along. You look like a man
it'll be a pleasure to do business with.

276
00:19:48,720 --> 00:19:49,914
Yes.

277
00:19:59,680 --> 00:20:02,672
HATTIE: Get out! You're not putting me out!

278
00:20:02,760 --> 00:20:06,196
I'll pay you me rent when I get it!

279
00:20:07,200 --> 00:20:09,316
HATTIE: Good morning, Father.
O'MALLEY: Good morning.

280
00:20:09,400 --> 00:20:12,472
Hello, Father.
Mrs. Quimp and I were just discussing you.

281
00:20:12,560 --> 00:20:15,552
- You were?
- As you know, I represent...

282
00:20:15,640 --> 00:20:17,835
the Knickerbocker Savings
and Loan Company.

283
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:20,354
Inasmuch as Mrs. Quimp
declines to pay her rent...

284
00:20:20,440 --> 00:20:22,431
the Knickerbocker Savings
and Loan Company...

285
00:20:22,520 --> 00:20:26,354
- refuses to offer her any further hospitality.
- Is she very far in arrears?

286
00:20:26,440 --> 00:20:28,715
TED: Mrs. Quimp has paid us nothing
for six months.

287
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:31,473
O'MALLEY: It's certainly very nice of you
to show her leniency.

288
00:20:31,560 --> 00:20:34,472
Supposing the poor old woman
has no place to go?

289
00:20:34,560 --> 00:20:38,678
The Knickerbocker Savings and Loan
Company is not a charitable institution...

290
00:20:38,760 --> 00:20:40,432
like St. Dominic's.

291
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:43,233
With us, it's just a matter
of cold-blooded business.

292
00:20:43,320 --> 00:20:47,108
With you it's different. You haven't got
anything and you don't want anything.

293
00:20:47,200 --> 00:20:49,839
That's your business
and people respect you for it.

294
00:20:49,920 --> 00:20:51,717
But I'm not in your business, see?

295
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:55,554
If I haven't got anything
and don't want anything, I'm a bum.

296
00:20:55,880 --> 00:20:58,235
Surely there must be something
we can do about it.

297
00:20:58,320 --> 00:21:02,393
I don't know what you'll do about it, but
I'm going to throw her right out on her ear.

298
00:21:02,480 --> 00:21:05,278
Give her a break.
Give her a month to make good in.

299
00:21:05,360 --> 00:21:08,432
- St. Dominic's will guarantee it.
- St. Dominic's?

300
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:10,756
I can see you haven't been around long.

301
00:21:10,840 --> 00:21:13,559
Why, St. Dominic's is in worse shape
than Mrs. Quimp.

302
00:21:13,640 --> 00:21:17,349
- My old man happens to own the mortgage...
- Your father holds the mortgage?

303
00:21:17,440 --> 00:21:18,555
You're darn right he does.

304
00:21:18,640 --> 00:21:21,074
Confidentially,
he'd like to find a way to foreclose.

305
00:21:21,160 --> 00:21:23,993
He wants to tear down the church
and make a parking lot of it.

306
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:27,072
Can you imagine it?
He's a very disliked man.

307
00:21:27,360 --> 00:21:30,511
- I'm sort of following in his footsteps.
- Junior?

308
00:21:30,880 --> 00:21:32,074
[Turkeys gobbling]

309
00:21:32,160 --> 00:21:33,673
HERMAN: It's turkeys.

310
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:41,834
TONY: Let's cut through the churchyard.

311
00:21:57,560 --> 00:21:59,232
[Turkey gobbles]

312
00:22:05,640 --> 00:22:07,995
FITZGIBBON: Good afternoon, boys.
BOYS: Hello, Father.

313
00:22:08,080 --> 00:22:10,833
That's a fine fat bird you have there.

314
00:22:10,920 --> 00:22:13,070
We was sort of bringing it over for you.

315
00:22:13,160 --> 00:22:16,357
- It's sort of a present. Ain't it, Herman?
- Yeah.

316
00:22:16,440 --> 00:22:20,069
That's very generous of you.
Such a fine bird and all.

317
00:22:20,560 --> 00:22:23,154
Now, where may I ask did you get it?

318
00:22:23,240 --> 00:22:26,118
- We got...
- We won it in a raffle over at the theatre.

319
00:22:26,200 --> 00:22:29,112
- We were lucky.
- Isn't that great?

320
00:22:30,440 --> 00:22:33,796
- But, surely, your mother...
- Except on Christmas, Ma don't like turkey.

321
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:35,029
- She don't?
- Honest.

322
00:22:35,120 --> 00:22:36,838
That's most fortunate for me.

323
00:22:36,920 --> 00:22:40,310
There's nothing I'm more partial to
than a nice tom turkey.

324
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:42,516
Roasted, all with dressing.

325
00:22:42,600 --> 00:22:45,478
I appreciate your kindness, boys.

326
00:22:45,560 --> 00:22:46,879
It ain't nothing, Father.

327
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:49,952
FITZGIBBON: On the contrary,
I appreciate the thought behind it.

328
00:22:50,040 --> 00:22:53,271
<i>Small luxuries, like small sacrifices,</i>
<i>are ofttimes the most godly.</i>

329
00:22:53,360 --> 00:22:55,715
Bless you both. Thank you.

330
00:23:00,440 --> 00:23:03,273
Take it inside the kitchen
to the housekeeper.

331
00:23:03,360 --> 00:23:05,749
HERMAN: Okay, Father, we'll see you later.

332
00:23:17,200 --> 00:23:19,395
FITZGIBBON: So you guaranteed
Mrs. Quimp's rent?

333
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:22,358
O'MALLEY: Of course.
FITZGIBBON: St. Dominic's can't afford it.

334
00:23:22,440 --> 00:23:25,910
I expected you to counsel Mrs. Quimp,
not to adopt her.

335
00:23:26,640 --> 00:23:27,755
[Exclaims contentedly]

336
00:23:27,840 --> 00:23:31,799
- Hot turkey.
- Hot? Of course it's hot.

337
00:23:32,880 --> 00:23:34,552
That's what I say.

338
00:23:48,080 --> 00:23:52,710
"Bless us, O Lord, for these Thy gifts
which we are about to receive. Amen."

339
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:53,915
Amen.

340
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:06,639
Say, Father, you know a youngster
around here named Tony Scaponi?

341
00:24:06,720 --> 00:24:08,870
FITZGIBBON: What about him?
O'MALLEY: This afternoon...

342
00:24:08,960 --> 00:24:12,635
Tony belongs to
a fine upstanding Catholic family.

343
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:17,910
Eleven children. Sure, I know Tony.
As fine a lad as there is in the parish.

344
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,319
Police don't think so.

345
00:24:19,400 --> 00:24:20,913
- They don't?
- No.

346
00:24:21,040 --> 00:24:23,429
If something isn't done
about Tony and his pals...

347
00:24:23,520 --> 00:24:25,556
they're gonna wind up in a reform school.

348
00:24:25,640 --> 00:24:27,517
- Who told you that?
- The police.

349
00:24:27,600 --> 00:24:30,353
You've been listening
to Patrick McCarthy, no doubt.

350
00:24:30,440 --> 00:24:34,718
Let me tell you that that man
hasn't been to Mass in the last <i>1</i>0 years.

351
00:24:35,160 --> 00:24:38,789
That may be, but I think
McCarthy's right about those kids.

352
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:41,792
They're terrorising
the whole neighbourhood.

353
00:24:42,320 --> 00:24:43,673
No use talking like that.

354
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:48,117
To hear the police talk, you'd think
that every lad in the parish was a criminal.

355
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:51,560
I'll have you know
that the very food there before us...

356
00:24:51,640 --> 00:24:55,997
is brought to us by two of those very lads
the police are so maliciously slandering.

357
00:24:56,080 --> 00:24:57,433
Is that so?

358
00:24:58,480 --> 00:25:00,710
Tony Scaponi was one of them.

359
00:25:01,920 --> 00:25:03,751
I gave them both my blessing.

360
00:25:03,840 --> 00:25:06,798
O'MALLEY: And they gave you the bird.
FITZGIBBON: Yeah.

361
00:25:08,080 --> 00:25:10,230
[O'Malley laughs heartily]

362
00:25:15,160 --> 00:25:16,878
[Doorbell buzzing]

363
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:18,553
I'll get it.

364
00:25:28,160 --> 00:25:30,754
O'MALLEY: Hello, McCarthy.
MCCARTHY: Good evening, Father.

365
00:25:30,840 --> 00:25:34,992
Well, I brung them.
Tony Scaponi, Herman Langerhanke.

366
00:25:35,080 --> 00:25:38,868
O'MALLEY: Hi, fellows.
I don't think you have to wait, McCarthy.

367
00:25:40,640 --> 00:25:42,073
Okay, Father.

368
00:25:45,560 --> 00:25:48,916
O'MALLEY: Say, I understand that
you fellows like baseball pretty well.

369
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,072
TONY: Yeah.
O'MALLEY: I was thinking, Saturday...

370
00:25:52,160 --> 00:25:55,596
the Yanks are playing the St. Louis Browns,
a doubleheader.

371
00:25:55,680 --> 00:25:58,990
Would you like to go out
and see the games with me?

372
00:25:59,280 --> 00:26:03,592
St. Louis is my old hometown, you know.
I'll get all the passes I want.

373
00:26:03,720 --> 00:26:06,393
- What do you say?
- Well, I guess so.

374
00:26:06,520 --> 00:26:08,829
Yeah, sure, I guess
the fellas would like that.

375
00:26:08,920 --> 00:26:11,639
It's a date then.
I'll meet you here Saturday at noon?

376
00:26:11,720 --> 00:26:12,948
That'd be good.

377
00:26:13,040 --> 00:26:16,794
You run along and have your dinner.
I'll go finish my turkey.

378
00:26:29,800 --> 00:26:31,995
Let me see now, where was I?

379
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:35,919
Oh, yeah, I know.
I was going to ask you something.

380
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:38,639
- What made me become a priest?
- No.

381
00:26:39,880 --> 00:26:43,236
About young Tony.
What was it the police accused him of?

382
00:26:43,320 --> 00:26:44,673
Stealing.

383
00:26:45,760 --> 00:26:49,389
- Stealing what?
- Turkeys.

384
00:26:59,320 --> 00:27:02,312
Seems the boys hijacked a poultry truck
down the street here.

385
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:07,030
There was quite a bit of excitement.
The driver reported them to the police.

386
00:27:08,080 --> 00:27:10,719
Did the poor man get his turkeys back?

387
00:27:12,560 --> 00:27:14,357
All but one, Father.

388
00:27:27,920 --> 00:27:29,478
[O'Malley clears throat]

389
00:27:33,440 --> 00:27:34,793
Thank you.

390
00:27:42,640 --> 00:27:45,029
[Playing sombre music]

391
00:27:51,880 --> 00:27:53,711
O'MALLEY: McCarthy, how are you?

392
00:27:53,800 --> 00:27:56,109
Good morning, Father.
You open for business?

393
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:58,919
Always open for business, McCarthy.
Come on in.

394
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:00,319
MCCARTHY: Come on.

395
00:28:07,560 --> 00:28:09,278
Come right in, Pat.

396
00:28:09,840 --> 00:28:11,876
- I got a problem, Father.
- Yeah?

397
00:28:11,960 --> 00:28:14,599
Seems like it's more yours than mine.

398
00:28:14,920 --> 00:28:18,879
It's her. Well, Father, it's this way.

399
00:28:20,040 --> 00:28:23,191
Last night I'm walking me beat, see?
Who do you think I runs into?

400
00:28:23,280 --> 00:28:25,111
- Her?
- Mrs. Quimp.

401
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:27,636
[Lmitating Hattie] "Officer McCarthy,"
she says.

402
00:28:27,720 --> 00:28:30,280
- You know how the old stool pigeon talks.
- Yes, I do.

403
00:28:30,360 --> 00:28:32,920
"If you'll go around the corner,
you'll find a girl.

404
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:35,560
"I've been watching her
and she ain't up to no good."

405
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:40,156
<i>Well, Father, I goes around the corner</i>
<i>and there, like the Quimp says, I finds her.</i>

406
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:43,389
MCCARTHY: Do you follow me, Father?
O'MALLEY: Yes.

407
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:47,470
Well, I looks at her and sizes her up.

408
00:28:48,480 --> 00:28:52,268
One of those things, I think.
I'm just about to say to her:

409
00:28:52,640 --> 00:28:55,473
"Look, sister, not on my beat."

410
00:28:56,160 --> 00:28:59,516
When she turns,
and right away I sees I'm out of line.

411
00:28:59,920 --> 00:29:02,115
- You follow me, Father?
- Yeah.

412
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:06,672
To get down to it, Father,
I find she's broke and run away from home.

413
00:29:07,720 --> 00:29:09,790
Doesn't know a soul in town.

414
00:29:09,880 --> 00:29:13,077
So, instead of booking her,
I takes her home.

415
00:29:13,160 --> 00:29:17,756
It's all right with the missus for one night,
but if she stays any longer...

416
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:20,149
I guess Mrs. McCarthy,
good woman that she is...

417
00:29:20,240 --> 00:29:22,071
is no different from any other woman.

418
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:23,991
- You follow me, Father?
- I follow you.

419
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:26,878
So, anyway, she tells us
that she's run away from home...

420
00:29:26,960 --> 00:29:29,269
on account of
her folks don't understand her.

421
00:29:29,360 --> 00:29:31,999
We tried arguing with her, Father,
but she's a tough one.

422
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:35,993
She thinks "Honour thy father
and thy mother" is a belly laugh.

423
00:29:36,080 --> 00:29:39,117
Well, Father, guess I'll let you
pick it up from here.

424
00:29:39,200 --> 00:29:42,192
MCCARTHY: Says her name's Carol James.
O'MALLEY: All right, McCarthy.

425
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:43,679
MCCARTHY: So long.
O'MALLEY: Goodbye.

426
00:29:43,760 --> 00:29:45,876
MCCARTHY: All right. You can go in now.

427
00:29:49,080 --> 00:29:51,958
Come right in.
Won't you sit down over here?

428
00:29:56,160 --> 00:29:59,755
Carol, suppose you give us
your version of it?

429
00:29:59,840 --> 00:30:01,717
I guess it's just about like he said.

430
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:04,234
- You don't get along with your parents?
- No.

431
00:30:04,320 --> 00:30:07,153
- So you're going to leave home?
- I've left.

432
00:30:07,680 --> 00:30:09,159
How are you fixed for funds?

433
00:30:09,240 --> 00:30:12,152
I haven't any.
That's how I met Officer McCarthy.

434
00:30:12,240 --> 00:30:13,832
But I'll get by.

435
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:20,711
- Why don't you go back home?
- I tell you, at home my life is intolerable.

436
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:23,468
O'MALLEY: Parents?
CAROL: We don't agree on anything.

437
00:30:23,560 --> 00:30:27,519
Don't like the way I do my hair,
my eyebrows, too much lipstick.

438
00:30:27,600 --> 00:30:32,116
Too something or other, too long, too short.
Do you think it's too short?

439
00:30:32,240 --> 00:30:35,198
Well, I don't know.

440
00:30:35,520 --> 00:30:37,272
They even object to my boyfriends.

441
00:30:37,360 --> 00:30:41,433
If they do let me go out, they say,
"Where are you going? Come home early.

442
00:30:41,560 --> 00:30:44,757
- "Come right home after the show."
- "No drive-in."

443
00:30:46,840 --> 00:30:49,752
No matter how early I get in, it's too late.

444
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:53,150
And if I say we ran out of gas,
they say I'm lying.

445
00:30:53,280 --> 00:30:56,078
- Are you?
- Sometimes.

446
00:30:57,400 --> 00:31:00,949
Did you ever think of maybe
having the boyfriends over to the house?

447
00:31:01,040 --> 00:31:02,996
[Sighing] Now you talk like they do.

448
00:31:03,080 --> 00:31:07,119
I can't have them over to the house
because Grandma sleeps in the living room.

449
00:31:07,200 --> 00:31:08,474
She does?

450
00:31:08,560 --> 00:31:10,790
By 9:00 we have to be off the couch.

451
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:14,236
She needs it for a bed. Can you imagine?

452
00:31:15,520 --> 00:31:17,988
Of course, you know,
there might be two sides to it.

453
