[Boys singing] <i>Three blind mice</i>

679
00:44:55,680 --> 00:44:59,309
<i>See how they run!</i>

680
00:44:59,400 --> 00:45:01,356
<i>They all ran after the farmer's wife</i>

681
00:45:01,440 --> 00:45:03,032
See what I mean?

682
00:45:05,200 --> 00:45:07,156
No, I've got to see the Bishop.

683
00:45:14,480 --> 00:45:17,199
O'MALLEY: We got our sections.
I'll give each section a note.

684
00:45:17,280 --> 00:45:19,794
O'MALLEY: Then we'll put them together
and have a chord.

685
00:45:19,880 --> 00:45:21,996
Take this section first. Here's your note.

686
00:45:22,080 --> 00:45:23,593
[Vocalising]

687
00:45:23,880 --> 00:45:25,677
Got that? Let me hear it now.

688
00:45:25,760 --> 00:45:26,875
[One boy harmonizing]

689
00:45:26,960 --> 00:45:30,157
I thought we had singers here.
Let's hear everybody in this section.

690
00:45:30,240 --> 00:45:32,231
Big, now, let me hear it.

691
00:45:32,440 --> 00:45:34,192
[Boys vocalising]

692
00:45:34,880 --> 00:45:37,155
O'MALLEY: That's good.
Second section, here's your note.

693
00:45:37,240 --> 00:45:39,151
[Vocalising]

694
00:45:39,600 --> 00:45:41,318
You got that? Let me hear it.

695
00:45:41,480 --> 00:45:43,277
[Boys vocalising]

696
00:45:43,760 --> 00:45:46,399
We got a cruller in there somewhere?
Who is that? You?

697
00:45:46,480 --> 00:45:48,232
O'MALLEY: What's your name?
ELMER: Elmer.

698
00:45:48,320 --> 00:45:50,117
Elmer, your voice is changing, isn't it?

699
00:45:50,200 --> 00:45:51,349
ELMER: I guess so, Father.

700
00:45:51,440 --> 00:45:54,432
Have to drop you down a bracket.
Get here in the third section.

701
00:45:54,520 --> 00:45:56,636
Elmer is a switch hitter, it seems.

702
00:45:56,840 --> 00:45:58,751
Let me hear that second section again.

703
00:45:59,880 --> 00:46:01,598
[Boys vocalising]

704
00:46:01,680 --> 00:46:04,478
That's great.
Now the third section. Here's your note.

705
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:06,274
Got that?

706
00:46:06,640 --> 00:46:08,278
[Boys vocalising]

707
00:46:08,480 --> 00:46:10,675
Elmer, you sing like
you're made for this section.

708
00:46:10,760 --> 00:46:13,752
Now we're gonna drop way down
in the basement. Watch. It's tricky.

709
00:46:13,840 --> 00:46:15,114
Everybody take a toehold.

710
00:46:15,200 --> 00:46:16,633
[Vocalising]

711
00:46:17,840 --> 00:46:20,195
That's your note. Let me hear it.

712
00:46:21,240 --> 00:46:23,037
[Boys vocalising]

713
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:26,673
O'MALLEY: There's a pink one somewhere.
TONY: That wasn't me.

714
00:46:26,760 --> 00:46:28,239
What did you sing?

715
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:29,913
[Tony's voice cracks]

716
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:31,672
[All laughing]

717
00:46:32,360 --> 00:46:33,475
[O'Malley clears throat]

718
00:46:33,560 --> 00:46:35,152
Sit down, Tony. Okay.

719
00:46:35,960 --> 00:46:38,110
Everybody together now.
You got your notes?

720
00:46:38,920 --> 00:46:41,992
We hit them all together
and we got a nice chord. Ready?

721
00:46:42,080 --> 00:46:44,548
Everybody take a deep breath now.

722
00:46:46,240 --> 00:46:47,753
Let's hear it.

723
00:46:48,280 --> 00:46:51,158
[All vocalising in harmony]

724
00:47:05,840 --> 00:47:08,991
O'MALLEY: You got chord number one,
chord number two, chord number three.

725
00:47:09,080 --> 00:47:11,674
O'MALLEY: Put those chords together
and we can sing a song.

726
00:47:11,760 --> 00:47:14,957
I'll hold up the fingers, they'll be
your signals. Watch the signals.

727
00:47:15,040 --> 00:47:18,476
Make out I'm the catcher.
I'm giving you the signals. One, two, three.

728
00:47:18,560 --> 00:47:20,039
<i>Ready? Here's your note now.</i>

729
00:47:20,120 --> 00:47:21,633
[O'Malley singing note]

730
00:47:22,480 --> 00:47:24,948
[O'Malley Singing] <i>Silent night</i>

731
00:47:25,120 --> 00:47:26,678
[Boys humming]

732
00:47:27,200 --> 00:47:31,671
<i>Holy night</i>

733
00:47:32,160 --> 00:47:37,029
<i>All is calm</i>

734
00:47:37,320 --> 00:47:41,916
<i>All is bright</i>

735
00:47:42,400 --> 00:47:51,399
<i>Round yon Virgin Mother and Child</i>

736
00:47:52,400 --> 00:48:01,877
<i>Holy Infant so tender and mild</i>

737
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:12,236
<i>Sleep in heavenly peace</i>

738
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:22,075
<i>Sleep in heavenly peace</i>

739
00:48:22,920 --> 00:48:25,434
That's fine, boys. Thanks very much.

740
00:48:26,360 --> 00:48:30,069
Want to call it a day? There's still
enough light outside for some baseball.

741
00:48:30,160 --> 00:48:32,628
BOY 3: Let's sing some more.
BOY 4: Yeah, let's go ahead.

742
00:48:32,720 --> 00:48:35,518
BOY 5: Yeah, come on!
BOY 6: Let's sing some more.

743
00:48:35,680 --> 00:48:37,272
[All agreeing]

744
00:48:40,880 --> 00:48:43,440
[Solemn instrumental music]

745
00:48:52,840 --> 00:48:55,434
- You saw the Bishop, Father?
- Yeah.

746
00:48:56,800 --> 00:49:01,351
Would you ask Father O'Malley
if he'd mind stepping into me study?

747
00:49:08,560 --> 00:49:11,199
[Solemn instrumental music continues]

748
00:49:16,040 --> 00:49:18,918
O'MALLEY: You wanted to see me, Father?
FITZGIBBON: Yes, so I did.

749
00:49:21,400 --> 00:49:22,674
Sit down.

750
00:49:30,800 --> 00:49:34,270
Father O'Malley, I've been to see the Bishop.

751
00:49:35,720 --> 00:49:37,153
Oh, you have?

752
00:49:39,240 --> 00:49:41,515
And I want to be frank with you.

753
00:49:42,520 --> 00:49:46,115
I must admit that my purpose
in going to see the Bishop...

754
00:49:46,520 --> 00:49:48,670
was to have you transferred.

755
00:49:56,080 --> 00:49:57,991
I'm sorry you don't like me, Father.

756
00:49:58,080 --> 00:50:02,790
I don't dislike anyone.
It's just that I disagree with you.

757
00:50:03,280 --> 00:50:04,998
What did the Bishop say?

758
00:50:05,080 --> 00:50:07,833
After a little talk, he congratulated me...

759
00:50:07,920 --> 00:50:10,593
on me 45 years at St. Dominic's.

760
00:50:11,920 --> 00:50:14,070
He has a remarkable memory.

761
00:50:15,280 --> 00:50:17,919
He said it was a monument...

762
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:21,629
to the fact that I had built it.

763
00:50:22,640 --> 00:50:25,677
Coming from the Bishop,
that's certainly a fine compliment.

764
00:50:25,760 --> 00:50:28,752
Then I told him
I had come to talk about you.

765
00:50:28,960 --> 00:50:31,076
That seemed to disturb him.

766
00:50:32,480 --> 00:50:35,517
<i>Then he started telling me</i>
<i>about what a fine young man you are.</i>

767
00:50:35,600 --> 00:50:39,115
<i>Capable, progressive,</i>
<i>how much confidence he had in you.</i>

768
00:50:40,600 --> 00:50:42,511
He even told me that...

769
00:50:43,440 --> 00:50:46,876
he had a nice talk with you
before you reported to me.

770
00:50:50,920 --> 00:50:54,390
Of course, he didn't tell me
what you two talked about.

771
00:50:54,800 --> 00:50:56,472
He didn't have to.

772
00:50:57,120 --> 00:50:59,759
I could see it in the good man's eyes.

773
00:51:02,240 --> 00:51:06,392
When you get to my age,
you can do that, you know. Oh, yes.

774
00:51:07,400 --> 00:51:11,154
<i>Then, after a little more telling me</i>
<i>how progressive you were...</i>

775
00:51:11,240 --> 00:51:13,117
<i>he asked me why I'd come.</i>

776
00:51:13,200 --> 00:51:16,590
And knowing what was on his mind
and to save him the embarrassment...

777
00:51:16,680 --> 00:51:18,636
of having to tell me...

778
00:51:18,800 --> 00:51:20,279
The Bishop.

779
00:51:20,560 --> 00:51:22,915
The Bishop wouldn't hurt anyone.

780
00:51:23,360 --> 00:51:25,237
I put him at his ease.

781
00:51:25,920 --> 00:51:27,638
"Bishop," I said...

782
00:51:28,120 --> 00:51:30,475
"the very thing that's on your mind
is on mine.

783
00:51:30,560 --> 00:51:33,677
"It's the very thing
I've come to see you about.

784
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:37,959
"I want you to put young Father O'Malley...

785
00:51:38,600 --> 00:51:40,795
"in charge of St. Dominic's."

786
00:51:41,480 --> 00:51:43,789
The Bishop seemed much relieved.

787
00:51:44,320 --> 00:51:47,596
He congratulated me on my ability to see...

788
00:51:47,680 --> 00:51:49,671
so clearly at my age...

789
00:51:51,240 --> 00:51:54,949
on my ability to face the inevitable.

790
00:51:57,240 --> 00:51:58,992
Then what happened?

791
00:51:59,760 --> 00:52:01,113
[Sniffs]

792
00:52:02,560 --> 00:52:03,993
That was all.

793
00:52:06,400 --> 00:52:10,473
O'MALLEY: Father, why can't we go along
just as we have been?

794
00:52:11,160 --> 00:52:13,310
No. You're in charge now.

795
00:52:15,840 --> 00:52:17,114
Sit down.

796
00:52:18,400 --> 00:52:19,753
No, Father.

797
00:52:19,840 --> 00:52:22,149
Sit down. I'll familiarise you with...

798
00:52:22,240 --> 00:52:25,915
O'MALLEY: There's no hurry about it.
We can do that anytime, Father.

799
00:52:26,760 --> 00:52:30,275
Is there anything you'd like me to do.
I mean, now?

800
00:52:30,520 --> 00:52:31,748
O'MALLEY: Nothing.

801
00:52:33,080 --> 00:52:34,513
Well, then...

802
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:40,079
if you don't mind,
I'll lie down a while before dinner.

803
00:52:40,160 --> 00:52:41,832
O'MALLEY: All right, Father.

804
00:52:45,440 --> 00:52:48,477
When you and the Bishop
had your little talk...

805
00:52:48,560 --> 00:52:51,120
it was more or less
along those lines, wasn't it?

806
00:52:51,200 --> 00:52:52,269
O'MALLEY: Yes.

807
00:53:08,320 --> 00:53:10,959
[Solemn instrumental music continues]

808
00:53:12,760 --> 00:53:16,958
I think you better start without him.
Looks like he's not coming down for dinner.

809
00:53:17,040 --> 00:53:19,713
He said he wanted to take a little nap.

810
00:53:19,800 --> 00:53:23,429
He didn't look well, did he,
when he came in this evening?

811
00:53:25,880 --> 00:53:29,714
Go see if he's awake.
If he's coming down, I'll wait for him.

812
00:53:34,480 --> 00:53:36,072
MRS. CARMODY: Father O'Malley!

813
00:53:36,280 --> 00:53:37,872
Father O'Malley!

814
00:53:39,400 --> 00:53:42,198
Father! He's gone.

815
00:53:42,440 --> 00:53:45,477
He's packed his things, everything.
He's gone.

816
00:53:45,720 --> 00:53:48,280
- Where would he go?
- I can't imagine.

817
00:53:58,880 --> 00:54:01,553
Okay, sure, but keep at it, will you?

818
00:54:03,120 --> 00:54:06,556
No, you can't miss him. A little guy. Old.

819
00:54:07,320 --> 00:54:09,436
Got a grip and an umbrella.

820
00:54:10,640 --> 00:54:11,755
Okay.

821
00:54:13,640 --> 00:54:17,758
Nothing yet, Father. They're gonna check
the subways, the hospitals.

822
00:54:17,840 --> 00:54:19,751
Look, Father, take it easy, will you?

823
00:54:19,840 --> 00:54:22,559
You better go home.
No use the two of us getting drowned.

824
00:54:22,640 --> 00:54:24,835
Call me the minute you hear anything.

825
00:54:24,920 --> 00:54:27,150
- I don't care what time it is.
- I will.

826
00:54:29,400 --> 00:54:30,071
[Clock ticking]

827
00:54:43,640 --> 00:54:45,710
MRS. CARMODY: Shall I make some coffee?

828
00:54:45,840 --> 00:54:47,432
[Exclaims questioningly]

829
00:54:47,560 --> 00:54:49,198
No, thank you.

830
00:54:59,600 --> 00:55:01,909
Come on. Now what's the matter?

831
00:55:06,400 --> 00:55:08,630
If you don't mind it,
I'd rather go in by myself.

832
00:55:08,720 --> 00:55:11,678
If you don't mind, I found you
and I'll deliver you personally.

833
00:55:11,760 --> 00:55:13,637
That's not necessary.

834
00:55:15,080 --> 00:55:17,275
There's no reward, you know.

835
00:55:17,600 --> 00:55:19,830
It's going to be a little difficult...

836
00:55:19,920 --> 00:55:23,196
and I'd rather explain to Father O'Malley
in me own way.

837
00:55:23,280 --> 00:55:25,748
And I can do that better
when you're not around.

838
00:55:25,840 --> 00:55:28,274
Okay. But if you want my advice...

839
00:55:28,360 --> 00:55:32,990
you just tell him you've been a bad boy,
you ran away from home and you're sorry.

840
00:55:33,400 --> 00:55:36,233
And if you want my advice,
you'll go to church on Sunday...

841
00:55:36,320 --> 00:55:40,393
and say you haven't been to Mass
in <i>1</i>0 years and that you're sorry.

842
00:55:42,760 --> 00:55:44,318
[Chuckles]

843
00:55:45,920 --> 00:55:47,876
[Clock ticking]

844
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:54,070
[Door opening]

845
00:56:27,640 --> 00:56:28,914
Hello.

846
00:56:35,120 --> 00:56:38,635
If you don't mind, I've come back,
but only temporarily.

847
00:56:39,920 --> 00:56:42,639
<i>Until me plans are more formulated...</i>

848
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:45,389
maybe you wouldn't mind letting me stay.

849
00:56:45,480 --> 00:56:47,516
I'll be no bother to you.

850
00:56:52,400 --> 00:56:55,995
Here, Father. Let's get out of these
wet clothes and get you up to bed.

851
00:56:56,080 --> 00:56:58,275
But I don't expect me old room.
That's yours now.

852
00:56:58,360 --> 00:57:01,113
- I haven't moved in there yet.
- I insist. That's your room.

853
00:57:01,200 --> 00:57:03,430
I'll sleep on a cot anywhere.

854
00:57:04,800 --> 00:57:07,872
FITZGIBBON: I'll not even be bothering you
for me food. I'll eat out.

855
00:57:07,960 --> 00:57:10,713
We'll talk later.
Mrs. Carmody will bring you something.

856
00:57:10,800 --> 00:57:14,839
- No. I'm not a bit hungry. I'll...
- Come on now, Father, just a wee snack.

857
00:57:14,920 --> 00:57:16,751
I've been keeping it for you on the stove.

858
00:57:16,840 --> 00:57:19,229
Nice juicy cut of roast beef,
Yorkshire pudding...

859
00:57:19,320 --> 00:57:21,231
and there were some creamed onions, too.

860
00:57:21,320 --> 00:57:23,515
And some asparagus
with buttered breadcrumbs.

861
00:57:23,600 --> 00:57:26,831
And golden brown potatoes
and a nice cup of coffee.

862
00:57:26,920 --> 00:57:29,115
Well, if you insist...

863
00:57:29,200 --> 00:57:32,351
just a small portion of everything.

864
00:57:40,160 --> 00:57:42,799
I hope it wasn't too much trouble for you,
Mrs. Carmody.

865
00:57:42,880 --> 00:57:46,111
- No trouble at all, Father.
- I feel I ought to help with the dishes.

866
00:57:46,200 --> 00:57:50,512
Don't worry about the dishes.
It isn't much washing they'll be needing.

867
00:57:55,120 --> 00:57:58,908
You're still a little cold, Father.
You were drenched to the skin.

868
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:00,752
You ought to take a little something
to warm you up.

869
00:58:02,240 --> 00:58:05,357
Do you have a wee drop
of the "crature" about?

870
00:58:08,480 --> 00:58:12,109
Matter of fact, I might have a little one
with you. I was out myself tonight.

871
00:58:12,200 --> 00:58:14,191
I went out for a paper.

872
00:58:16,120 --> 00:58:17,792
Well, in that case...

873
00:58:17,880 --> 00:58:22,510
- I'll ask Mrs. Carmody where she keeps it.
- No. Look yonder in the bookcase.

874
00:58:25,240 --> 00:58:27,754
<i>No, the other side. Now down.</i>

875
00:58:28,520 --> 00:58:31,671
You'll find it behind
<i>The Life of General Grant.</i>

876
00:58:43,680 --> 00:58:46,274
[Music box playing Irish lullaby]

877
00:58:53,680 --> 00:58:55,477
A bit of old Ireland?

878
00:58:56,240 --> 00:59:00,631
Yes. Every Christmas since I left,
my old mother sends me one of these.

879
00:59:04,160 --> 00:59:07,550
With a degree of abstinence,
it becomes me calendar.

880
00:59:07,720 --> 00:59:12,032
I get a little behind during Lent,
but it comes out even at Christmas.

881
00:59:35,880 --> 00:59:37,472
That's me mother.

882
00:59:38,200 --> 00:59:39,679
O'MALLEY: She's very beautiful.

883
00:59:39,760 --> 00:59:43,514
Of course that was taken some time ago.
She's 90 now.

884
00:59:44,600 --> 00:59:48,718
Let's drink to your mother.
Hope you'll be seeing her soon, Father.

885
00:59:49,800 --> 00:59:51,756
What about your mother?

886
00:59:52,240 --> 00:59:56,711
I don't remember much about her.
She died when I was quite young.

887
01:00:03,480 --> 01:00:06,153
Let's drink to the two of them, anyway.

888
01:00:07,160 --> 01:00:08,912
Thank you, Father.

889
01:00:16,880 --> 01:00:18,757
You know, Father O'Malley...

890
01:00:18,880 --> 01:00:22,668
I always planned
that as soon as I got a few dollars ahead...

891
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:26,197
I'd go back to the old country
and see my mother.

892
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:30,959
Now, would you believe it,
that was 45 years ago...

893
01:00:31,920 --> 01:00:34,434
and every time I get a few dollars ahead...

894
01:00:34,520 --> 01:00:38,479
There's always somebody
that seems to need it more than you do.

895
01:00:39,080 --> 01:00:42,038
You'd like her. She'd like you, too.

896
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:45,434
She always had a song in her heart.

897
01:00:46,760 --> 01:00:49,149
I can almost hear her now.

898
01:00:50,320 --> 01:00:52,470
[Music box playing]

899
01:00:59,760 --> 01:01:03,719
Me boy, do you know <i>Too Ra Loo Ra Loo?</i>

900
01:01:04,520 --> 01:01:08,195
[Singing] <i>Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral</i>

901
01:01:09,360 --> 01:01:12,158
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-li</i>

902
01:01:13,360 --> 01:01:16,830
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral</i>

903
01:01:17,560 --> 01:01:21,235
<i>Hush now, don't you cry</i>

904
01:01:22,520 --> 01:01:25,796
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral</i>

905
01:01:26,880 --> 01:01:29,997
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-li</i>

906
01:01:30,840 --> 01:01:34,196
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral</i>

907
01:01:34,920 --> 01:01:39,038
<i>That's an Irish lullaby</i>

908
01:01:40,040 --> 01:01:43,350
<i>Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral</i>

909
01:01:44,160 --> 01:01:46,720
[Humming tune]

910
01:02:33,680 --> 01:02:35,079
FITZGIBBON: Good night.

911
01:02:35,840 --> 01:02:37,353
[Laughs softly]

912
01:02:51,600 --> 01:02:54,751
Take it easy, boys.
Here, Tony, here's the fare.

913
01:02:54,840 --> 01:02:57,400
O'MALLEY: Everybody right home
and to bed. Get a lot of rest.

914
01:02:57,480 --> 01:03:00,836
I'm responsible for you. Don't forget
we got a rehearsal in the morning.

915
01:03:00,920 --> 01:03:03,639
- Aren't you coming with us?
- No, I think I'll walk home.

916
01:03:03,720 --> 01:03:05,597
I want to think about my sermon for Sunday.

917
01:03:05,680 --> 01:03:08,148
- It'll be extra special for your parents.
- Oh, good.

918
01:03:08,240 --> 01:03:10,231
On how to bring up children.

919
01:03:10,720 --> 01:03:12,676
Father! Good luck to you!

920
01:03:13,240 --> 01:03:15,549
[Children's voices harmonizing]

921
01:03:26,160 --> 01:03:27,309
Chuck.

922
01:03:29,040 --> 01:03:32,237
- Jenny!
- Chuck, it's good to see you.

923
01:03:32,320 --> 01:03:34,390
It's good to see you, too.

924
01:03:34,800 --> 01:03:38,429
- Where were you going, Jenny?
- To work, and I'm late. Come along.

925
01:03:39,920 --> 01:03:42,480
[Musical instruments being tuned]

926
01:03:50,600 --> 01:03:51,794
MAN: Gangway.

927
01:03:58,920 --> 01:04:01,070
What are you doing here?
This is the Metropolitan.

928
01:04:01,160 --> 01:04:04,755
- This is where I work.
- Wait a minute. Isn't that <i>Carmen?</i>

929
01:04:06,520 --> 01:04:07,873
[Laughs heartily]

930
01:04:07,960 --> 01:04:10,713
What do you play,
one of the spectators at the bullfight?

931
01:04:10,800 --> 01:04:13,030
Believe it or not, I'm Carmen.

932
01:04:13,320 --> 01:04:14,912
O'MALLEY: Jenny Tuffle, Carmen?

933
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:16,911
I've changed that. It's Genevieve Linden.

934
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:19,514
I was singing Carmen in Rio
and they heard me and said:

935
01:04:19,600 --> 01:04:21,795
"Would you sing it here?"
Here. Can you imagine?

936
01:04:21,880 --> 01:04:24,599
- Jenny Tuffle at the Metropolitan.
- Imagine that.

937
01:04:24,680 --> 01:04:28,559
Well, Chuck, make yourself comfortable.
I have to be getting on with it.

938
01:04:30,240 --> 01:04:32,356
It's good to see you, Chuck.

939
01:04:32,440 --> 01:04:34,954
[Soft instrumental music]

940
01:04:35,320 --> 01:04:37,834
Come on, Effie, I'm terribly late.

941
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:42,355
I don't know why I'm even talking to you.

942
01:04:42,440 --> 01:04:44,635
O'MALLEY: No?
JENNY: Why didn't you write?

943
01:04:45,240 --> 01:04:48,994
- I did write.
- I know you did, but why did you stop?

944
01:04:51,720 --> 01:04:55,349
O'MALLEY: Didn't I tell you?
JENNY: No, you didn't, but you're going to.

945
01:05:00,600 --> 01:05:03,956
Jenny? Please, I want to ask you
just a small favour.

946
01:05:04,520 --> 01:05:06,511
Hello, Tommy. What is it?

947
01:05:06,600 --> 01:05:10,752
Tonight, would you be so good
as to glance occasionally at my baton?

948
01:05:11,120 --> 01:05:13,190
Tonight, let's not race.

949
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:16,833
Let's try just for once to finish together?

950
01:05:16,920 --> 01:05:17,955
[Jenny laughs]

951
01:05:18,040 --> 01:05:21,999
JENNY: All right, Tommy,
I promise. And, Tommy, do me a favour.

952
01:05:22,560 --> 01:05:26,075
<i>Meet Chuck O'Malley.</i>
<i>He's a very old friend of mine.</i>

953
01:05:26,280 --> 01:05:28,953
<i>Chuck,</i> Signor <i>Tommaso Bozanni.</i>

954
01:05:29,040 --> 01:05:31,474
Father. "Chuck"?

955
01:05:31,560 --> 01:05:33,551
She always calls me that.

956
01:05:35,320 --> 01:05:38,596
You haven't told me yet, Chuck.
Why did you stop writing?

957
01:05:38,680 --> 01:05:41,069
I did tell you in my last letter.

958
01:05:42,320 --> 01:05:44,117
Which letter was that?

959
01:05:46,400 --> 01:05:49,836
I guess that must have been
the letter you didn't get.

960
01:05:50,800 --> 01:05:53,678
You wrote to me in Rome, in Florence...

961
01:05:54,080 --> 01:05:57,231
Naples, Vienna, Budapest.

962
01:05:58,600 --> 01:06:02,388
Then I went to Switzerland, and I found
your letter waiting for me in Lucerne.

963
01:06:02,480 --> 01:06:05,153
You should have been there, Chuck.

964
01:06:05,240 --> 01:06:08,869
<i>It was a week before Christmas</i>
<i>and there was a quaint little post office.</i>

965
01:06:08,960 --> 01:06:11,190
<i>I walked up to it in the snow.</i>

966
01:06:11,760 --> 01:06:15,673
The moon was so bright
that I read your letter on the way home.

967
01:06:16,040 --> 01:06:18,315
And I answered it that night.

968
01:06:18,680 --> 01:06:21,353
But that letter in Lucerne
was the last one I got.

969
01:06:21,480 --> 01:06:23,994
From there I went to South America.

970
01:06:24,400 --> 01:06:26,709
But there were no more letters.

971
01:06:27,800 --> 01:06:29,631
<i>What happened, Chuck?</i>

972
01:06:29,840 --> 01:06:32,354
[Soft instrumental music continues]

973
01:06:32,840 --> 01:06:34,432
Chuck, what...

974
01:06:37,720 --> 01:06:39,119
Father Chuck.

975
01:06:45,320 --> 01:06:48,517
It'll take me a little while to get used to that.

976
01:06:49,760 --> 01:06:51,478
Where's your parish, Father?

977
01:06:51,560 --> 01:06:55,189
I'm over here at St. Dominic's,
about <i>1</i>0 blocks from here.

978
01:06:58,800 --> 01:07:00,597
O'MALLEY: You remember Timmy?

979
01:07:00,960 --> 01:07:03,918
Tim O'Dowd? Yes, of course, I do.

980
01:07:04,440 --> 01:07:07,398
He's at St. Francis now. He's a priest, too.

981
01:07:08,280 --> 01:07:11,078
Dear old Timmy. Can you imagine that?

982
01:07:11,560 --> 01:07:14,120
Well, I'll have to be running along.

983
01:07:15,400 --> 01:07:18,949
Please don't go.
Tommy, he can stand in the wings, can't he?

984
01:07:19,040 --> 01:07:21,554
TOMMY: It would be a privilege.
JENNY: Please.

985
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:23,638
You know, Tommy...

986
01:07:24,680 --> 01:07:28,070
Father O'Malley was the first one
to tell me I could sing.

987
01:07:28,160 --> 01:07:30,799
Maybe one day I'll tell her the same thing.

988
01:07:30,880 --> 01:07:33,758
If she listens to you,
maybe you could persuade her...

989
01:07:33,840 --> 01:07:36,229
to listen just once to me.

990
01:07:36,320 --> 01:07:37,958
Watch the baton.

991
01:07:39,040 --> 01:07:41,349
Good luck, Miss Tuffle.

992
01:07:50,680 --> 01:07:53,114
[Singing opera song]

993
01:08:19,320 --> 01:08:21,675
[Chorus singing]

994
01:10:35,080 --> 01:10:37,310
[Audience applauding]

995
01:10:53,080 --> 01:10:55,594
- You wanted to see me, Father?
- Yeah.

996
01:10:56,160 --> 01:10:59,516
Mrs. Quimp here, good woman that she is...

997
01:10:59,800 --> 01:11:02,075
has come here
with a bit of disturbing information.

998
01:11:02,160 --> 01:11:05,152
I think it should more properly
be brought to your attention.

999
01:11:05,240 --> 01:11:07,629
Nice work, Mrs. Quimp. What is it?

1000
01:11:07,720 --> 01:11:11,030
Suppose you tell Father O'Malley
in your own words.

1001
01:11:11,880 --> 01:11:14,110
You'd better tell him, Father.

1002
01:11:18,680 --> 01:11:20,955
Your little songbird
who was without funds...

1003
01:11:21,040 --> 01:11:23,952
but not a bit interested
in general housework...

1004
01:11:24,400 --> 01:11:27,073
is feathering her nest in her own manner.

1005
01:11:27,160 --> 01:11:31,472
And if Mrs. Quimp's observations
are correct, a very fine manner it is.

1006
01:11:31,640 --> 01:11:34,871
It seems, Father O'Malley,
that the young lady in question...

1007
01:11:34,960 --> 01:11:37,872
has an apartment directly across the street.

1008
01:11:37,960 --> 01:11:40,997
Opposite Mrs. Quimp's bedroom.

1009
01:11:42,320 --> 01:11:46,711
According to Mrs. Quimp, young Ted Haines
comes early and stays so late that...

1010
01:11:46,800 --> 01:11:49,394
Mrs. Quimp is losing a lot of sleep.

1011
01:11:50,520 --> 01:11:52,670
It's queer, isn't it, Father?

1012
01:11:53,200 --> 01:11:57,432
Young Haines was ready to throw me out
without so much as a "How do you do?"

1013
01:11:57,840 --> 01:12:00,274
But when it comes to this young lady...

1014
01:12:00,360 --> 01:12:03,796
and mark you, there are other words
I could call her...

1015
01:12:03,880 --> 01:12:05,916
he acts quite different.

1016
01:12:06,160 --> 01:12:08,276
Don't you think it's strange?

1017
01:12:08,360 --> 01:12:11,318
That's a question.
People do funny things, you know.

1018
01:12:11,400 --> 01:12:14,836
Fine goings-on, Father O'Malley.
It's as plain as the nose on your face.

1019
01:12:14,920 --> 01:12:17,195
The nose on whose face, Father?

1020
01:12:17,720 --> 01:12:21,474
It doesn't matter whose face it's on.
You and I have got to face it.

1021
01:12:22,240 --> 01:12:23,673
Excuse us.

1022
01:12:28,360 --> 01:12:31,397
This is very serious business,
Father O'Malley.

1023
01:12:31,480 --> 01:12:35,712
As you're more familiar with the case,
I think you should handle it.

1024
01:12:36,440 --> 01:12:38,635
I'll handle the little sins.

1025
01:12:44,240 --> 01:12:48,358
[Singing] <i>All through a lifetime</i>

1026
01:12:49,520 --> 01:12:54,469
<i>I'll be loving you and then</i>

1027
01:12:55,160 --> 01:13:00,109
<i>On the day after forever</i>

1028
01:13:03,480 --> 01:13:07,996
<i>I'll just begin</i>

1029
01:13:08,960 --> 01:13:11,918
<i>again</i>

1030
01:13:13,080 --> 01:13:14,513
[Knocking on door]

1031
01:13:14,600 --> 01:13:15,874
Come in.

1032
01:13:16,760 --> 01:13:18,990
CAROL: Hello, Father.
O'MALLEY: Hello, Carol.

1033
01:13:21,360 --> 01:13:23,157
- Hi, Father.
- Hello.

1034
01:13:24,760 --> 01:13:27,991
- I heard you. That's more like it.
- Thank you, Father.

1035
01:13:28,080 --> 01:13:31,755
Maybe it's because I'm putting
more meaning into the words.

1036
01:13:35,560 --> 01:13:37,630
O'MALLEY: Very nice here, isn't it?

1037
01:13:41,200 --> 01:13:42,519
Very nice.

1038
01:13:48,960 --> 01:13:51,997
- Before you go any further...
- You mean it's all in my mind?

1039
01:13:52,080 --> 01:13:53,559
That's right.

1040
01:13:55,280 --> 01:13:59,239
Yes, I'm sure Father is just dying
to hear more of the details.

1041
01:13:59,720 --> 01:14:01,756
- Yes.
- Won't you sit down?

1042
01:14:08,560 --> 01:14:11,597
I was going down the street,
minding my own business, too...

1043
01:14:11,680 --> 01:14:15,389
when who do you think just happened by,
purely by accident, of course...

1044
01:14:15,480 --> 01:14:17,357
and pulled up alongside of the curb?

1045
01:14:17,440 --> 01:14:19,476
- Ted Haines, Jr.
- Right.

1046
01:14:19,560 --> 01:14:23,030
And what do you think his approach was?
You tell him.

1047
01:14:23,680 --> 01:14:27,559
- I prefer not to remember.
- Well, being a woman, I do.

1048
01:14:27,640 --> 01:14:30,552
His exact words were,
"Hey, good-looking, what's cooking?"

1049
01:14:30,640 --> 01:14:32,153
Now wait a minute.

1050
01:14:32,240 --> 01:14:35,755
<i>What I really said was,</i>
<i>"Who do you know that I know?"</i>

1051
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:37,433
You know, that's worse.

1052
01:14:38,120 --> 01:14:39,519
Well, that was that.

1053
01:14:39,600 --> 01:14:43,195
And with practically no more of a build up
than that, he asked me to lunch.

1054
01:14:43,320 --> 01:14:46,232
Who knows? It might have worked.
It's been known to.

1055
01:14:46,320 --> 01:14:49,551
So after I'd cooled him off, I came back here.

1056
01:14:49,640 --> 01:14:52,393
No job, no money,
expecting to be thrown out any minute.

1057
01:14:52,480 --> 01:14:56,314
There was a knock on the door. I said
to myself, "The landlord. Here it comes."

1058
01:14:56,400 --> 01:14:58,755
- And who do you think was there?
- Junior?

1059
01:14:58,840 --> 01:15:01,957
- Right. I was so surprised.
- So was I.

1060
01:15:03,080 --> 01:15:05,719
Well, up to here, we're all surprised.

1061
01:15:06,720 --> 01:15:10,110
Naturally, before throwing me out,
he had to know a little about me.

1062
01:15:10,200 --> 01:15:13,795
So in a few well-chosen sentences,
I gave him the details.

1063
01:15:13,880 --> 01:15:15,791
Sort of like I told you.

1064
01:15:15,960 --> 01:15:18,599
And you found a landlord
with a heart of gold.

1065
01:15:18,680 --> 01:15:21,672
Well, not exactly a heart of gold,
Father, but...

1066
01:15:21,800 --> 01:15:25,918
Well, we had the apartment vacant,
and it seemed a shame to throw her out.

1067
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:30,278
- Anyway, what's wrong with that?
- Nothing that I know of, up to here.

1068
01:15:31,360 --> 01:15:34,511
As I was saying,
it was a shame to throw her out.

1069
01:15:34,880 --> 01:15:36,074
Like Mrs. Quimp?

1070
01:15:36,160 --> 01:15:39,516
Yeah. No! Well, that's different.

1071
01:15:40,440 --> 01:15:42,431
I can see that, obviously.

1072
01:15:43,280 --> 01:15:47,558
She told me about coming to see you
and that you wanted to help her.

1073
01:15:47,640 --> 01:15:50,313
You don't have a corner on helping people,
do you?

1074
01:15:50,480 --> 01:15:53,153
<i>And besides, I've practically</i>
<i>got her lined up in a job.</i>

1075
01:15:53,240 --> 01:15:55,959
Yes, and as soon as I get it,
I'm going to pay him back.

1076
01:15:56,040 --> 01:15:58,952
Every nickel of it. You too, Father.

1077
01:15:59,840 --> 01:16:01,592
No hurry about me.

1078
01:16:02,240 --> 01:16:04,754
Rather a nice-looking piano you have here.

1079
01:16:04,840 --> 01:16:07,400
Well, she needs one, doesn't she?

1080
01:16:07,480 --> 01:16:10,517
- She's got to practice. She's a singer.
- It was very thoughtful.

1081
01:16:10,600 --> 01:16:13,478
Of course, pianos are a little expensive
these days.

1082
01:16:14,280 --> 01:16:17,272
I asked her first
if she couldn't play a ukulele.

1083
01:16:17,360 --> 01:16:20,352
- Well, then naturally...
- Yeah, naturally.

1084
01:16:21,480 --> 01:16:23,232
Carol tells me you can play, Father.

1085
01:16:23,320 --> 01:16:25,834
How about trying it out
to see if I got a good buy?

1086
01:16:25,920 --> 01:16:28,434
Yes, play something for us, Father.

1087
01:16:31,960 --> 01:16:34,235
[Playing soft music]

1088
01:16:39,200 --> 01:16:41,794
Would you mind us asking you
a few questions, Father?

1089
01:16:41,880 --> 01:16:44,599
- No.
- Where'd you get that wicked left hand?

1090
01:16:44,680 --> 01:16:47,148
Well, I've always been interested in music.

1091
01:16:47,240 --> 01:16:50,038
Used to write a bit of it at school.
I had a little band.

1092
01:16:50,120 --> 01:16:52,759
We used to play for the school dances.

1093
01:16:53,360 --> 01:16:55,112
O'Malley's Orioles.

1094
01:16:55,200 --> 01:16:56,792
[Playing upbeat music]

1095
01:16:57,120 --> 01:17:00,430
You know, at one time
I had quite a decision to make:

1096
01:17:00,520 --> 01:17:04,672
Whether to write the nation's songs
or go my way.

1097
01:17:06,360 --> 01:17:09,352
- Any regrets, Father?
- Regrets? No.

1098
01:17:09,440 --> 01:17:12,557
I get a great happiness
out of helping people realise that...

1099
01:17:12,640 --> 01:17:14,949
religion doesn't have to be this.

1100
01:17:15,040 --> 01:17:16,678
[Playing sombre music]

1101
01:17:16,760 --> 01:17:19,320
Taking all the fun out of everything.

1102
01:17:19,400 --> 01:17:21,072
It can be bright.

1103
01:17:21,640 --> 01:17:25,030
Bring you closer to happiness.
Do you go to church, Ted?

1104
01:17:26,120 --> 01:17:28,918
<i>Or would you rather I change the subject?</i>

1105
01:17:30,120 --> 01:17:33,078
If I could just express musically
what I have in my mind...

1106
01:17:33,160 --> 01:17:35,435
it would be much more eloquent.

1107
01:17:36,600 --> 01:17:39,592
It would sound simpler,
and you'd remember it.

1108
01:17:40,320 --> 01:17:43,357
Sometimes the spoken word
can be pretty dull.

1109
01:17:44,120 --> 01:17:46,634
You mean, sing your sermons, Father?

1110
01:17:47,240 --> 01:17:48,434
Yeah, sort of.

1111
01:17:48,520 --> 01:17:50,192
CAROL: Have you
had anything published?

1112
01:17:50,280 --> 01:17:51,315
No.

1113
01:17:52,680 --> 01:17:55,672
Will you play us
one of your unpublished ones?

1114
01:18:04,760 --> 01:18:08,992
[Singing] <i>This road leads to Rainbowville</i>

1115
01:18:11,200 --> 01:18:13,270
<i>going my way?</i>

1116
01:18:14,440 --> 01:18:19,036
<i>Up ahead is Bluebird Hill</i>

1117
01:18:20,640 --> 01:18:22,949
<i>going my way?</i>

1118
01:18:24,920 --> 01:18:29,675
<i>Just pack a basket full of wishes</i>

1119
01:18:31,160 --> 01:18:34,596
<i>and off you start</i>

1120
01:18:35,480 --> 01:18:38,278
<i>With Sunday morning</i>

1121
01:18:38,720 --> 01:18:42,633
<i>in your heart</i>

1122
01:18:44,800 --> 01:18:49,316
<i>Round the bend you'll see a sign</i>

1123
01:18:50,680 --> 01:18:53,069
<i>"Dreamer's Highway"</i>

1124
01:18:54,680 --> 01:18:59,310
<i>Happiness is down the line</i>

1125
01:19:00,480 --> 01:19:02,835
<i>going my way?</i>

1126
01:19:05,040 --> 01:19:07,634
<i>The smiles you gather</i>

1127
01:19:08,080 --> 01:19:10,275
<i>will look well</i>

1128
01:19:10,840 --> 01:19:13,877
<i>on you</i>

1129
01:19:15,600 --> 01:19:18,956
<i>Oh, I hope you're</i>

1130
01:19:20,280 --> 01:19:23,636
<i>going my way</i>

1131
01:19:24,600 --> 01:19:27,956
<i>too</i>

1132
01:19:37,720 --> 01:19:40,109
I think I'll leave you on that.

1133
01:19:45,320 --> 01:19:47,675
Goodbye, Carol. Goodbye, Ted.

1134
01:19:49,280 --> 01:19:50,633
TED: Bye, Father.

1135
01:19:51,720 --> 01:19:53,153
[Door opens]

1136
01:19:55,200 --> 01:19:56,474
[Door shuts]

1137
01:19:56,800 --> 01:19:58,233
Nice thought.

1138
01:19:59,800 --> 01:20:01,392
<i>Going My Way.</i>

1139
01:20:04,160 --> 01:20:05,434
Isn't it?

1140
01:20:11,400 --> 01:20:13,152
He's quite a fellow.

1141
01:20:19,520 --> 01:20:22,830
O'DOWD: Good morning, Father.
I'd like to present Miss Genevieve Linden.

1142
01:20:22,920 --> 01:20:25,639
- Jenny, this is Father Fitzgibbon.
- Good morning, Father.

1143
01:20:25,720 --> 01:20:28,075
- How do you do?
- She's a singer.

1144
01:20:29,800 --> 01:20:31,358
[Exclaims inquiringly]

1145
01:20:32,200 --> 01:20:34,475
- Looking for work?
- No, Father.

1146
01:20:35,040 --> 01:20:37,508
She sings at the Metropolitan Opera House.

1147
01:20:37,800 --> 01:20:41,315
Well, it's a great privilege to meet you,
Miss Linden.

1148
01:20:41,560 --> 01:20:43,516
You've come quite a ways in the world.

1149
01:20:43,600 --> 01:20:45,670
- Travelled extensively?
- Yes, quite a bit.

1150
01:20:45,760 --> 01:20:48,911
- Where's your home?
- I just bought a home in Long Island.

1151
01:20:49,000 --> 01:20:50,797
- A nice home?
- Very lovely.

1152
01:20:50,880 --> 01:20:54,839
In that case, you'd be interested
in a crazy quilt. We're raffling it off.

1153
01:20:55,600 --> 01:20:56,749
Again?

1154
01:20:56,840 --> 01:20:58,193
[Clicking tongue]

1155
01:20:58,280 --> 01:21:00,953
We're trying to raise a little money,
Father O'Dowd.

1156
01:21:01,040 --> 01:21:02,029
I see.

1157
01:21:02,120 --> 01:21:05,317
- How many?
- I'll take them all. How much are they?

1158
01:21:07,960 --> 01:21:09,188
Be $<i>1</i>0.

1159
01:21:11,080 --> 01:21:13,469
- Thank you, and I hope you win it.
- Thank you.

1160
01:21:13,560 --> 01:21:17,473
And I hope you win it, too, Jenny.
Then perhaps you'll donate it to our church.

1161
01:21:17,560 --> 01:21:20,028
O'DOWD: And we can raffle it off over there
all over again.

1162
01:21:20,120 --> 01:21:23,430
I'd hate to see that crazy quilt
leaving the parish.

1163
01:21:23,920 --> 01:21:25,876
O'DOWD: Where's the pied piper
and his merry men?

1164
01:21:25,960 --> 01:21:26,949
Down in the basement.

1165
01:21:27,040 --> 01:21:28,268
Thank you, Father. Come, Jenny.

1166
01:21:28,360 --> 01:21:30,032
- Goodbye, Father.
- Goodbye. Thank you.

1167
01:21:30,120 --> 01:21:33,078
Congratulations on selling all your tickets.

1168
01:21:36,720 --> 01:21:38,950
[All singing]

1169
01:21:43,960 --> 01:21:47,270
Like some more?
You're our first audience, you know.

1170
01:21:47,360 --> 01:21:48,793
Ready, boys?

1171
01:21:49,080 --> 01:21:51,196
[All singing]

1172
01:22:00,680 --> 01:22:03,558
- That's the best.
- Of course, we have our more serious side.

1173
01:22:03,640 --> 01:22:06,791
Would you like to hear something nice,
something with more beauty?

1174
01:22:06,880 --> 01:22:08,393
Yes, very much.

1175
01:22:09,880 --> 01:22:11,950
[Playing solemn music]

1176
01:22:13,960 --> 01:22:16,554
[All singing hymn]

1177
01:24:12,400 --> 01:24:16,075
- Very well done, boys. That's all.
- Thank you so much.

1178
01:24:16,280 --> 01:24:17,793
O'MALLEY: See you all tomorrow.

1179
01:24:20,840 --> 01:24:22,432
They're angels.

1180
01:24:22,760 --> 01:24:25,991
They've got something you lose
when you get older.

1181
01:24:28,920 --> 01:24:31,388
- What's the matter, Timmy?
- Nothing.

1182
01:24:31,560 --> 01:24:33,835
That was beautiful, Chuck. Beautiful.

1183
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:38,073
Of course, we don't get Genevieve Linden
of the Metropolitan every day.

1184
01:24:38,160 --> 01:24:41,709
- Nor Deems O'Dowd either.
- Now wait a minute.

1185
01:24:42,120 --> 01:24:45,510
I'm glad to see you've kept up
your interest in music, Father.

1186
01:24:46,000 --> 01:24:47,797
Are you writing anything anymore?

1187
01:24:47,880 --> 01:24:51,919
Yes. I have a little song here
that Timmy's going to take to a publisher.

1188
01:24:52,000 --> 01:24:53,228
A very good friend of his.

1189
01:24:53,320 --> 01:24:57,108
If he likes it, that might be the answer
to all our troubles.

1190
01:24:59,280 --> 01:25:02,829
I have bad news. I've been to the publisher.
He wasn't interested.

1191
01:25:02,920 --> 01:25:06,196
Wouldn't even look at it.
Said they were loaded up.

1192
01:25:07,280 --> 01:25:08,793
May I see it?

1193
01:25:13,800 --> 01:25:16,633
- So you're still in trouble.
- Wouldn't even look at it?

1194
01:25:16,720 --> 01:25:19,154
- He glanced at it.
- What'd he have to say?

1195
01:25:19,640 --> 01:25:23,633
- "Schmaltz isn't selling this season."
- What are they buying?

1196
01:25:23,960 --> 01:25:26,349
- "Barfola."
- No, I think they call it "Voffala."

1197
01:25:26,440 --> 01:25:27,873
Yeah, Voffala.

1198
01:25:28,280 --> 01:25:30,396
Boy, I heard some of their song hits.

1199
01:25:30,480 --> 01:25:33,711
<i>It Was Hut-Sut Time On The Rilla-Rye.</i>

1200
01:25:35,480 --> 01:25:38,517
<i>And then there was another one.</i>
<i>I couldn't understand the words.</i>

1201
01:25:38,600 --> 01:25:41,068
This fella lost his girl in Salt Lake City.

1202
01:25:41,160 --> 01:25:44,357
Then he goes on to say
the altitude is 5,400 feet.

1203
01:25:44,800 --> 01:25:46,313
The average temperature, 73.

1204
01:25:46,400 --> 01:25:49,437
The section is noted for gold, silver,
copper, grain.

1205
01:25:49,520 --> 01:25:51,988
But that doesn't make
any difference to this fella...

1206
01:25:52,080 --> 01:25:54,275
because he's lost his sugar.

1207
01:25:54,560 --> 01:25:58,678
- Voffala.
- Well, I know what Voffala is. It's...

1208
01:25:59,400 --> 01:26:01,709
[Playing upbeat jazzy tune]

1209
01:26:04,880 --> 01:26:07,599
- What's the matter with that?
- Not from me.

1210
01:26:08,560 --> 01:26:12,599
Can you imagine <i>Beat Me Eight To The Bar</i>
by Daddy O'Malley?

1211
01:26:18,680 --> 01:26:21,638
- I like this.
- She's buying schmaltz.

1212
01:26:23,560 --> 01:26:26,552
<i>Going My Way.</i>
Will you autograph it for me?

1213
01:26:26,760 --> 01:26:28,079
All right.

1214
01:26:30,120 --> 01:26:31,553
Thank you.

1215
01:26:32,320 --> 01:26:33,639
I have to go now.

1216
01:26:33,720 --> 01:26:36,712
JENNY: Father Tim, can I drop you off?
O'DOWD: You can, thank you.

1217
01:26:40,360 --> 01:26:41,634
O'MALLEY: There you are.

1218
01:26:47,120 --> 01:26:48,189
Thank you.

1219
01:26:48,280 --> 01:26:50,555
O'MALLEY: Thank you.
JENNY: Goodbye.

1220
01:26:50,640 --> 01:26:51,914
O'MALLEY: Goodbye.

1221
01:26:55,360 --> 01:26:57,954
- My pen, Father.
- Yes.

1222
01:26:58,240 --> 01:26:59,912
- Good day.
- Good day.

1223
01:27:16,640 --> 01:27:18,312
[Haines exclaims sheepishly]

1224
01:27:18,400 --> 01:27:19,549
Yes?

1225
01:27:29,680 --> 01:27:31,671
[Exclaims inquisitively]

1226
01:27:39,120 --> 01:27:40,872
[Exclaims knowingly]

1227
01:27:43,480 --> 01:27:45,198
Well, who are you?

1228
01:27:46,000 --> 01:27:49,072
I want to have a talk with you.
That's who I am.

1229
01:27:49,160 --> 01:27:50,639
[Exclaims in delight]

1230
01:27:50,720 --> 01:27:52,631
You must be his father.

1231
01:27:54,120 --> 01:27:57,351
- How old are you?
- I'm <i>1</i>8.

1232
01:27:57,440 --> 01:27:59,192
Well, that's good.

1233
01:28:08,640 --> 01:28:11,074
CAROL: Ted!
TED: Be right with you, darling.

1234
01:28:13,080 --> 01:28:14,798
[Humming]

1235
01:28:30,520 --> 01:28:31,839
TED: What?

1236
01:28:35,120 --> 01:28:36,519
[Laughing] Hello, Dad.

1237
01:28:41,400 --> 01:28:44,119
Where have you been
for the past two weeks?

1238
01:28:44,200 --> 01:28:45,599
Well, Dad...

1239
01:28:47,880 --> 01:28:50,758
I've been in a blue heaven
dancing on a pink cloud.

1240
01:28:50,840 --> 01:28:54,435
- She came in on a moonbeam.
- That's a lie. I had you followed.

1241
01:28:54,520 --> 01:28:58,798
That wasn't cricket. When you were my age,
I didn't follow you around.

1242
01:29:02,200 --> 01:29:04,270
Everything I say kills her.

1243
01:29:04,520 --> 01:29:07,478
It kills me, too. Do you realise
this is one of my apartments?

1244
01:29:07,560 --> 01:29:09,755
Yes. I had it redecorated.

1245
01:29:09,840 --> 01:29:13,276
- And that's one of my robes.
- Yes, I had it altered.

1246
01:29:13,920 --> 01:29:15,797
I'm going to like him.

1247
01:29:16,280 --> 01:29:18,840
Do you know I could have you
thrown out of town?

1248
01:29:18,920 --> 01:29:21,388
Maybe I know something about her
you don't know.

1249
01:29:21,480 --> 01:29:23,630
She was picked up on the street
by the police.

1250
01:29:23,720 --> 01:29:25,119
I know that.

1251
01:29:25,200 --> 01:29:28,875
Maybe we know something
that you don't know. We're married.

1252
01:29:30,280 --> 01:29:31,508
Married?

1253
01:29:33,680 --> 01:29:35,318
I'll have that annulled.

1254
01:29:35,520 --> 01:29:38,910
You can only get them annulled
when they aren't right in the first place.

1255
01:29:39,000 --> 01:29:40,228
Ours was right.

1256
01:29:40,600 --> 01:29:44,275
We said something about,
"'Till death do us part." Remember?

1257
01:29:46,200 --> 01:29:49,397
HAINES: Where were you married?
TED: St. Dominic's, Father O'Malley.

1258
01:29:49,640 --> 01:29:52,518
O'Malley! A secret marriage?

1259
01:29:52,600 --> 01:29:54,989
Well, he's put his foot in it this time.

1260
01:29:55,240 --> 01:29:57,993
It wasn't a secret marriage.
It was in all the papers.

1261
01:29:58,080 --> 01:29:59,479
HAINES: I didn't see it.

1262
01:29:59,560 --> 01:30:01,357
You never get past the financial column.

1263
01:30:01,720 --> 01:30:03,312
Don't be impertinent!

1264
01:30:03,480 --> 01:30:06,278
Young woman, do you know
how he's planned to support you?

1265
01:30:06,360 --> 01:30:07,873
You know he's quit his job?

1266
01:30:07,960 --> 01:30:10,758
That's all right. I'll support him.

1267
01:30:12,160 --> 01:30:13,752
Sure, she's working.

1268
01:30:16,200 --> 01:30:17,838
You'd live off your wife?

1269
01:30:17,920 --> 01:30:21,708
Mother was a big help to you, wasn't she,
until you got on your feet?

1270
01:30:23,360 --> 01:30:26,750
That was entirely different.
I made something of myself.

1271
01:30:32,600 --> 01:30:34,477
Yes, Dad, you certainly have.

1272
01:30:35,480 --> 01:30:38,552
Look, Son. My boy.

1273
01:30:40,720 --> 01:30:42,790
Have you no family pride?

1274
01:30:43,080 --> 01:30:44,877
[Exclaims negatively]

1275
01:30:46,000 --> 01:30:47,752
HAINES: No shame?
TED: Nope.

1276
01:30:48,440 --> 01:30:51,591
You've certainly slipped, my boy.
You've lost everything.

1277
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:54,912
I don't think so, Dad.
I think I've found something.

1278
01:30:56,560 --> 01:30:58,198
[Exclaims affirmatively]

1279
01:31:02,200 --> 01:31:05,237
Well, darling, I guess I'd better get dressed.

1280
01:31:16,200 --> 01:31:18,270
I think I'm a failure as a father.

1281
01:31:19,160 --> 01:31:20,559
I don't think so.

1282
01:31:21,200 --> 01:31:23,395
TED: Darling, where's my hat?

1283
01:31:24,840 --> 01:31:26,239
I'll get it.

1284
01:31:54,040 --> 01:31:56,270
[Soft instrumental music]

1285
01:31:57,560 --> 01:32:00,677
You'll have to forgive the way
we've been acting today, Dad.

1286
01:32:00,760 --> 01:32:02,512
We were a little hysterical.

1287
01:32:02,600 --> 01:32:05,398
I guess we were both a little, well, mad.

1288
01:32:05,800 --> 01:32:07,518
Well, I'm mad, too.

1289
01:32:08,480 --> 01:32:12,234
Quitting his job like that.
Running off and getting married.

1290
01:32:12,440 --> 01:32:16,228
I don't know. This younger generation
doesn't seem to have any sense.

1291
01:32:50,400 --> 01:32:51,879
So long, sweet.

1292
01:32:53,320 --> 01:32:54,833
God bless you.

1293
01:33:00,120 --> 01:33:03,476
Goodbye, Dad.
That plane you gave me did the trick.

1294
01:33:04,600 --> 01:33:09,116
When they found out about my 600 hours
in the air, they said, "Bud, we want you in."

1295
01:33:11,240 --> 01:33:13,708
Be nice to her, Dad. She'll grow on you.

1296
01:33:17,360 --> 01:33:18,793
[Whispering] Goodbye, boy.

1297
01:33:18,960 --> 01:33:20,393
[Carol sobs]

1298
01:33:30,160 --> 01:33:32,913
He's gone, Dad.

1299
01:33:40,840 --> 01:33:44,230
Max, you have to do this for me
and I don't want any arguments about it.

1300
01:33:44,320 --> 01:33:47,949
I'm afraid we got all the songs we need.
Our catalogue is full.

1301
01:33:48,040 --> 01:33:51,112
Now wait a minute.
I've been to a lot of trouble to arrange this.

1302
01:33:51,200 --> 01:33:54,112
So grab your hat and a taxi
and get right over here.

1303
01:33:54,760 --> 01:33:56,591
Yes, now. This very minute.

1304
01:33:56,680 --> 01:33:59,319
If you don't, I'll put the Irish curse on you.

1305
01:34:00,480 --> 01:34:02,038
Goodbye, Father.

1306
01:34:02,920 --> 01:34:05,388
That's Father O'Dowd, a friend of mine.

1307
01:34:05,480 --> 01:34:07,596
- What did he want? A donation?
- No.

1308
01:34:07,680 --> 01:34:11,195
Pal of his has got a song,
and he's plugging it. And what a plug.

1309
01:34:11,800 --> 01:34:15,190
He's grabbed off the Metropolitan
Opera House with the full orchestra...

1310
01:34:15,280 --> 01:34:18,431
conducted by this fellow Tommaso...

1311
01:34:18,760 --> 01:34:23,390
whatever his name is. The star,
Genevieve Linden and a choir of 30 voices.

1312
01:34:24,000 --> 01:34:26,878
All this fuss to put over a song
written by a pal of his.

1313
01:34:26,960 --> 01:34:29,155
And they're waiting right now
for us at the Met.

1314
01:34:29,240 --> 01:34:32,152
MAN: At the Metropolitan?
MAX: Can you imagine such a thing?

1315
01:34:33,320 --> 01:34:35,754
[Orchestra playing]

1316
01:34:42,440 --> 01:34:47,230
[Singing] <i>This road leads to Rainbowville</i>

1317
01:34:47,400 --> 01:34:50,790
<i>going my way?</i>

1318
01:34:50,880 --> 01:34:55,158
<i>Up ahead is Bluebird Hill</i>

1319
01:34:55,560 --> 01:34:58,996
<i>going my way?</i>

1320
01:34:59,480 --> 01:35:04,429
<i>Just pack a basket full of wishes</i>

1321
01:35:04,920 --> 01:35:07,878
<i>and off you start</i>

1322
01:35:07,960 --> 01:35:10,838
<i>With Sunday morning</i>

1323
01:35:10,920 --> 01:35:15,914
<i>in your heart</i>

1324
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:20,993
<i>Round the bend you'll see a sign</i>

1325
01:35:22,200 --> 01:35:25,397
<i>"Dreamer's Highway"</i>

1326
01:35:25,480 --> 01:35:29,234
<i>Happiness is down the line</i>

1327
01:35:30,480 --> 01:35:33,916
<i>going my way?</i>

1328
01:35:34,160 --> 01:35:36,230
<i>The smiles you gather</i>

1329
01:35:36,320 --> 01:35:38,754
<i>will look well</i>

1330
01:35:39,280 --> 01:35:44,274
<i>on you</i>

1331
01:35:46,360 --> 01:35:49,557
<i>Oh, I hope you're</i>

1332
01:35:49,800 --> 01:35:54,237
<i>going my way</i>

1333
01:35:54,960 --> 01:35:57,952
<i>too</i>

1334
01:35:58,040 --> 01:36:02,158
[Boys singing] <i>Round the bend</i>
<i>you'll see a sign</i>

1335
01:36:03,480 --> 01:36:06,711
<i>"Dreamer's Highway"</i>

1336
01:36:06,800 --> 01:36:11,316
<i>Happiness is down the line</i>

1337
01:36:12,240 --> 01:36:15,437
<i>going my way?</i>

1338
01:36:16,080 --> 01:36:17,911
<i>The smiles you gather</i>

1339
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:20,036
<i>will look well</i>

1340
01:36:20,400 --> 01:36:25,349
<i>on you</i>

1341
01:36:29,120 --> 01:36:32,635
<i>Oh, I hope you're</i>

1342
01:36:32,720 --> 01:36:37,669
<i>going my way</i>

1343
01:36:38,840 --> 01:36:43,834
<i>too</i>

1344
01:36:59,200 --> 01:37:01,668
That's very good. Wonderful.

1345
01:37:01,880 --> 01:37:03,757
MAX: You sang it great.
JENNY: Thank you.

1346
01:37:03,840 --> 01:37:06,229
- That's a pretty good song you got there.
- Thank you.

1347
01:37:06,320 --> 01:37:08,595
- I guess you ought to know.
- You bet he does.

1348
01:37:08,680 --> 01:37:11,672
They say he's the sharpest little man
in town.

1349
01:37:13,800 --> 01:37:17,429
- I'm embarrassed.
- You mean to talk business? The money?

1350
01:37:18,360 --> 01:37:21,113
Don't let that embarrass you. We love it.

1351
01:37:21,800 --> 01:37:24,439
What I wanted to say is that,
although it's great...

1352
01:37:24,520 --> 01:37:25,999
it's just as I told you, Father.

1353
01:37:26,080 --> 01:37:28,992
It's too good for us. It's way over our head.

1354
01:37:29,400 --> 01:37:32,631
You see, it's not just the type of song
that a guy would...

1355
01:37:32,720 --> 01:37:35,314
Pardon me, Father, that a gentleman...

1356
01:37:35,400 --> 01:37:38,233
would croon to his babe,
if you know what I mean.

1357
01:37:38,320 --> 01:37:40,914
It doesn't say enough. It hasn't got that...

1358
01:37:42,280 --> 01:37:44,077
Well, it's just not for me.

1359
01:37:44,160 --> 01:37:48,278
I think you ought to try it out on someone
who publishes higher class stuff.

1360
01:37:48,360 --> 01:37:49,509
Thanks.

1361
01:37:49,720 --> 01:37:52,518
Well, I guess we'd better
get back to the office.

1362
01:37:53,160 --> 01:37:55,390
You know, Father, I could be wrong.

1363
01:37:55,480 --> 01:37:58,472
- I hope I am. Goodbye.
- Goodbye.

1364
01:38:01,040 --> 01:38:03,998
- I'm sorry.
- Well, we tried.

1365
01:38:05,200 --> 01:38:07,953
You sang it beautifully, Jenny.
Boys, you did fine.

1366
01:38:08,040 --> 01:38:10,076
O'MALLEY: Not one mistake.
BOYS: Thank you, Father.

1367
01:38:10,160 --> 01:38:12,799
If that isn't good,
I'll go into the real estate business.

1368
01:38:12,880 --> 01:38:15,792
I was going to ask you
and the boys to sing a little more...

1369
01:38:15,880 --> 01:38:18,440
but maybe you don't feel like it now.

1370
01:38:18,520 --> 01:38:22,672
They sing divinely,
and they look like Botticelli's angels.

1371
01:38:23,040 --> 01:38:24,996
Maybe a little something?

1372
01:38:26,640 --> 01:38:29,154
- What do you think they'd like to hear?
<i>- The Mule.</i>

1373
01:38:29,240 --> 01:38:30,514
<i>- The Mule.</i>
<i>- The Mule?</i>

1374
01:38:30,600 --> 01:38:32,716
- Yeah.
- Is that all right with you?

1375
01:38:36,040 --> 01:38:37,996
[All singing]

1376
01:38:42,120 --> 01:38:44,998
[Singing] <i>Would you like to swing on a star</i>

1377
01:38:45,080 --> 01:38:48,231
<i>Carry moonbeams home in a jar</i>

1378
01:38:48,760 --> 01:38:51,115
<i>And be better off than you are</i>

1379
01:38:52,680 --> 01:38:55,399
<i>Or would you rather be a mule</i>

1380
01:38:55,480 --> 01:38:59,029
<i>A mule is an animal with long funny ears</i>

1381
01:38:59,120 --> 01:39:02,032
<i>He kicks up at anything he hears</i>

1382
01:39:02,120 --> 01:39:05,396
<i>His back is brawny but his brain is weak</i>

1383
01:39:05,520 --> 01:39:08,034
<i>He's just plain stupid with a stubborn streak</i>

1384
01:39:08,120 --> 01:39:11,271
<i>And by the way, if you hate to go to school</i>

1385
01:39:12,120 --> 01:39:14,190
<i>You may grow up to be a mule</i>

1386
01:39:14,280 --> 01:39:17,477
[Boys singing] <i>Or would you like to</i>
<i>swing on a star</i>

1387
01:39:17,560 --> 01:39:20,757
<i>Carry moonbeams home in a jar</i>

1388
01:39:20,840 --> 01:39:24,958
<i>And be better off than you are</i>

1389
01:39:25,040 --> 01:39:27,873
<i>Or would you rather be a pig</i>

1390
01:39:27,960 --> 01:39:31,032
<i>A pig is an animal with dirt on his face</i>

1391
01:39:31,120 --> 01:39:34,510
<i>His shoes are a terrible disgrace</i>

1392
01:39:34,600 --> 01:39:37,717
<i>He has no manners when he eats his food</i>

1393
01:39:37,800 --> 01:39:40,360
<i>He's fat and lazy and extremely rude</i>

1394
01:39:40,440 --> 01:39:44,274
<i>But if you don't care a feather or a fig</i>

1395
01:39:44,360 --> 01:39:46,669
<i>You may grow up to be a pig</i>

1396
01:39:46,760 --> 01:39:49,991
<i>Or would you like to swing on a star</i>

1397
01:39:50,080 --> 01:39:53,277
<i>Carry moonbeams home in a jar</i>

1398
01:39:53,360 --> 01:39:57,353
<i>And be better off than you are</i>

1399
01:39:57,440 --> 01:40:00,193
<i>Or would you rather be a fish</i>

1400
01:40:00,280 --> 01:40:03,511
<i>A fish won't do anything,</i>
<i>but swim in a brook</i>

1401
01:40:03,600 --> 01:40:06,592
<i>He can't write his name or read a book</i>

1402
01:40:06,680 --> 01:40:09,638
<i>To fool the people is his only thought</i>

1403
01:40:09,720 --> 01:40:12,678
<i>Yeah, but even though he's slippery,</i>
<i>he still gets caught</i>

1404
01:40:12,760 --> 01:40:16,594
<i>But then if that sort of life is what you wish</i>

1405
01:40:16,680 --> 01:40:18,955
<i>You may grow up to be a fish</i>

1406
01:40:19,040 --> 01:40:22,237
<i>And all the monkeys aren't in the zoo</i>

1407
01:40:22,320 --> 01:40:25,710
<i>Every day you meet quite a few</i>

1408
01:40:25,800 --> 01:40:28,109
<i>So you see it's all up to you</i>

1409
01:40:30,200 --> 01:40:33,272
<i>You can be better than you are</i>

1410
01:40:35,760 --> 01:40:38,274
<i>You could be swingin' on a star</i>

1411
01:40:46,320 --> 01:40:49,392
- Is that your song, Father?
- Yes.

1412
01:40:49,480 --> 01:40:51,869
Well, we'll take a flier on that.

1413
01:40:51,960 --> 01:40:53,951
Did you hear that, Timmy?

1414
01:40:54,040 --> 01:40:55,519
[Laughing excitedly]

1415
01:40:55,600 --> 01:40:57,352
O'DOWD: You're a grand lad.

1416
01:40:58,320 --> 01:41:01,153
I knew your name wasn't Dolan for nothing.

1417
01:41:04,280 --> 01:41:06,396
Fellas, if you'll come to St. Dominic's...

1418
01:41:06,480 --> 01:41:08,994
- tomorrow morning at <i>1</i>0:30.
- Church?

1419
01:41:09,080 --> 01:41:11,878
Max, a day in church
isn't gonna hurt you that much.

1420
01:41:11,960 --> 01:41:13,678
Be there, and bring the cash with you.

1421
01:41:13,760 --> 01:41:16,115
Father O'Malley will tell you
how he wants it paid.

1422
01:41:16,200 --> 01:41:20,591
An old man, dear friend of Father O'Malley's
is involved in this: Father Fitzgibbon.

1423
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:25,790
It would make Father O'Malley very happy
if you fellas would just do this his way.

1424
01:41:26,240 --> 01:41:28,037
- Church?
- Church.

1425
01:41:31,400 --> 01:41:36,235
FITZGIBBON: As you know,
I've been here for 45 years.

1426
01:41:36,600 --> 01:41:38,670
Forty-six in October.

1427
01:41:40,640 --> 01:41:43,598
And during that time...

1428
01:41:43,680 --> 01:41:47,355
I've always asked you to be generous,
which you have.

1429
01:41:47,440 --> 01:41:49,795
<i>And now I have to ask you again.</i>

1430
01:41:50,360 --> 01:41:53,318
<i>You all know how I feel about St. Dominic's.</i>

1431
01:41:55,040 --> 01:41:57,998
<i>Well, we're in dire financial stress.</i>

1432
01:42:00,560 --> 01:42:02,471
<i>So give what you can.</i>

1433
01:42:02,560 --> 01:42:06,314
And I know that whatever you give...

1434
01:42:07,320 --> 01:42:11,393
whether it's large or small,
the good Lord will bless you for it.

1435
01:42:12,680 --> 01:42:16,355
In the name of the Father, the Son,
and the Holy Ghost. Amen.

1436
01:42:17,400 --> 01:42:19,470
[Choir singing]

1437
01:43:15,360 --> 01:43:17,669
Very gratifying.

1438
01:43:18,560 --> 01:43:20,391
And the Bishop thought I couldn't preach.

1439
01:43:20,480 --> 01:43:23,597
Thought I had a mouthful of clover.
I wish he'd been here.

1440
01:43:23,680 --> 01:43:26,319
Father, now that you're practically
wallowing in wealth...

1441
01:43:26,400 --> 01:43:28,914
do you suppose I could have a half a dollar?

1442
01:43:29,000 --> 01:43:30,672
What for?

1443
01:43:30,760 --> 01:43:34,389
Father O'Dowd and I thought, with
your permission, we'd play golf tomorrow.

1444
01:43:34,480 --> 01:43:35,993
I need a new golf ball.

1445
01:43:36,080 --> 01:43:38,833
If I lose it, I'll swear off. I'll quit.

1446
01:43:39,040 --> 01:43:43,158
Take 50 cents. No.
Take it out of the ladies' sodality.

1447
01:43:43,240 --> 01:43:44,639
They never keep any books.

1448
01:43:44,720 --> 01:43:47,712
You suppose I could buy
Father O'Dowd one, too?

1449
01:43:48,920 --> 01:43:52,276
- Must we?
- I can get two nice repaints for 50 cents.

1450
01:43:53,240 --> 01:43:54,309
Give him 50 cents.

1451
01:43:54,400 --> 01:43:57,233
- You ought to come along with us.
- You don't have to play.

1452
01:43:57,320 --> 01:43:58,719
Just go around.

1453
01:43:58,800 --> 01:44:01,439
- The fresh air will do you good.
- You can be our kibitzer.

1454
01:44:01,520 --> 01:44:02,714
- Your what?
- Kibitzer.

1455
01:44:02,800 --> 01:44:06,190
- What's a kibitzer?
- A sort of over-the-shoulder quarterback.

1456
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:10,468
- Will you come?
- A little fresh air might do me good.

1457
01:44:10,560 --> 01:44:12,994
- We'll get a ball for you, too.
- Of course.

1458
01:44:20,800 --> 01:44:23,109
FITZGIBBON: Plenty of mushrooms
around here.

1459
01:44:35,760 --> 01:44:38,274
FITZGIBBON: Where did that go?
O'MALLEY: Right there.

1460
01:44:45,880 --> 01:44:49,998
FITZGIBBON: Now, let me understand.
If you get the ball in the hole...

1461
01:44:50,080 --> 01:44:52,992
- in less hits than Father O'Dowd...
- I win.

1462
01:44:53,080 --> 01:44:55,435
FITZGIBBON: So you've got to count
the number of blows?

1463
01:44:55,520 --> 01:44:58,956
That's right, Father. Step aside.
He's gonna play now. Careful.

1464
01:45:20,440 --> 01:45:22,670
How many did you have? Three?

1465
01:45:22,760 --> 01:45:24,034
FITZGIBBON: How many?

1466
01:45:40,640 --> 01:45:42,676
That's remarkable.

1467
01:45:42,760 --> 01:45:45,752
- Can you do that every time?
- I've been known to miss, Father.

1468
01:45:45,840 --> 01:45:48,308
A strong crosswind or something.

1469
01:45:48,400 --> 01:45:51,517
- Here, give me a holt of that.
- You wanna try it?

1470
01:45:53,480 --> 01:45:56,153
Wait, I'll throw a ball in there for you.
There you are.

1471
01:45:56,240 --> 01:45:59,550
Keep your head down now, Father.
Watch your language.

1472
01:46:18,800 --> 01:46:20,677
Father, you holed out.

1473
01:46:21,280 --> 01:46:22,713
Not bad for a beginner.

1474
01:46:22,800 --> 01:46:24,995
- You've played before.
- No, believe me.

1475
01:46:25,080 --> 01:46:28,277
That's the first time
I ever had a caddy in me hand.

1476
01:46:28,360 --> 01:46:31,193
Well, you better play and I'll watch then.

1477
01:46:36,200 --> 01:46:37,918
[O 'Dowd humming]

1478
01:47:22,200 --> 01:47:24,191
[Fitzgibbon humming]

1479
01:47:26,600 --> 01:47:28,556
[O'Malley humming]

1480
01:47:40,400 --> 01:47:42,709
I guess I better be going.

1481
01:47:43,720 --> 01:47:46,792
Let that be a lesson to you, Father.
Don't trust anyone.

1482
01:47:47,080 --> 01:47:49,036
[Laughs]

1483
01:47:53,920 --> 01:47:57,754
- What an extraordinary person.
- Isn't he?

1484
01:48:02,160 --> 01:48:05,118
FITZGIBBON: Well, I'll sleep well
tonight, anyway.

1485
01:48:07,360 --> 01:48:09,430
Think it must be that golf.

1486
01:48:10,560 --> 01:48:14,235
Shades of me childhood.
You know, I feel <i>1</i>0 years younger.

1487
01:48:15,320 --> 01:48:19,518
You know, I was thinking, Father.
Now that everything is going so right...

1488
01:48:19,680 --> 01:48:23,355
before something goes wrong,
you ought to take a little time off.

1489
01:48:23,640 --> 01:48:25,232
To do what, for instance?

1490
01:48:25,320 --> 01:48:29,233
Well, like, for instance, take a trip home
and see your mother.

1491
01:48:29,960 --> 01:48:32,474
The interest is all paid up to date.

1492
01:48:32,680 --> 01:48:37,515
Unless something goes wrong, I have plans
that'll take care of the next payment.

1493
01:48:38,080 --> 01:48:40,878
You really think it would be all right?

1494
01:48:41,160 --> 01:48:42,798
I mean, that you'll take...

1495
01:48:42,880 --> 01:48:45,519
Father Fitzgibbon! Chuck!
The church is afire!

1496
01:48:45,840 --> 01:48:47,990
[Fire engine alarm ringing]

1497
01:49:14,240 --> 01:49:16,959
Don't worry, Father. We'll build again.

1498
01:49:27,840 --> 01:49:31,515
O'MALLEY: Can I help you, Father?
FITZGIBBON: No, it's all right. I can manage.

1499
01:49:33,760 --> 01:49:35,637
It's for the birds.

1500
01:49:36,840 --> 01:49:39,354
[Solemn instrumental music]

1501
01:49:43,600 --> 01:49:45,795
They're used to coming here.

1502
01:49:47,600 --> 01:49:50,068
- I don't want them to go away.
- No.

1503
01:49:51,440 --> 01:49:55,115
You see, Father? They're not leaving.
Nobody's leaving you.

1504
01:49:56,560 --> 01:50:00,997
And when your church is rebuilt,
they'll all be back. Everyone will be back.

1505
01:50:01,080 --> 01:50:04,789
In the meantime, you can send
your congregation over to my parish.

1506
01:50:04,880 --> 01:50:08,190
I'll split the collection with you. 50-50.

1507
01:50:08,280 --> 01:50:09,872
Take it, Father.

1508
01:50:11,320 --> 01:50:16,075
Now what makes you all so hopeful
that the church will ever be rebuilt?

1509
01:50:16,160 --> 01:50:18,469
[Ominous instrumental music]

1510
01:50:22,080 --> 01:50:24,036
- You're supposed to take this.
- No, I can't.

1511
01:50:24,120 --> 01:50:25,712
- Come on, please. Take it.
- No.

1512
01:50:25,800 --> 01:50:29,349
I'll tell you what, if you'll take it,
I'll take some, too.

1513
01:50:30,400 --> 01:50:33,915
- There, now that wasn't so bad.
- [Exclaiming] Don't you try it.

1514
01:50:34,680 --> 01:50:36,352
Doctors. Medicine.

1515
01:50:36,840 --> 01:50:40,549
- What I need is to be up and about.
- Being up and about is what got you down.

1516
01:50:40,640 --> 01:50:43,916
Tramping all over the parish to raise funds.
How much did you collect?

1517
01:50:44,000 --> 01:50:46,594
There's no need for you to rub it in.

1518
01:50:46,920 --> 01:50:49,593
- $35.85.
- Yeah.

1519
01:50:50,280 --> 01:50:52,555
- How much is the doctor's bill?
- $40.

1520
01:50:53,320 --> 01:50:55,788
Says here to take two.
We wanna get our money's worth.

1521
01:50:55,880 --> 01:50:59,714
Listen. There's nothing in that bottle
that's going to do me any good.

1522
01:50:59,800 --> 01:51:02,234
Now you're not gonna lose hope, are you?

1523
01:51:02,320 --> 01:51:03,514
Hope?

1524
01:51:06,120 --> 01:51:10,272
Chuck, when you're young, it's easy to keep
the fires of hope burning bright.

1525
01:51:11,520 --> 01:51:16,310
But at my age, you're lucky if the pilot light
doesn't go out.

1526
01:51:19,320 --> 01:51:22,949
I know, Father, 45 years
of your efforts in ashes.

1527
01:51:24,880 --> 01:51:26,472
Here, take this.

1528
01:51:30,840 --> 01:51:32,910
That'll keep the pilot light burning.

1529
01:51:33,000 --> 01:51:35,992
Yes, it ought to.
Tastes like it had kerosene in it.

1530
01:51:36,080 --> 01:51:37,433
[Chuckles]

1531
01:51:37,960 --> 01:51:40,872
- Well, did you make your parish calls?
- Yes.

1532
01:51:40,960 --> 01:51:43,520
Mrs. McGonigle's rheumatism
is kicking up again.

1533
01:51:43,600 --> 01:51:45,989
I told her to bury a potato in the backyard.

1534
01:51:46,080 --> 01:51:48,230
- That's for warts.
- That's what she said.

1535
01:51:48,320 --> 01:51:50,834
And I heard Mrs. Quimp's new gossip.

1536
01:51:50,920 --> 01:51:55,311
- What else?
- Then I went to see Carol and Mr. Haines.

1537
01:51:55,400 --> 01:51:58,915
- Did they hear from young Ted?
- Young Ted has been wounded in Africa.

1538
01:51:59,000 --> 01:52:01,514
- Too bad.
- They're shipping him home.

1539
01:52:02,240 --> 01:52:04,754
Fine, upstanding young fella.

1540
01:52:04,840 --> 01:52:07,513
- Maybe they'll decorate him.
- No, I doubt it.

1541
01:52:08,280 --> 01:52:11,078
Some friend of his ran over him in a jeep.

1542
01:52:11,600 --> 01:52:13,591
But I've got some good news.

1543
01:52:13,680 --> 01:52:18,515
- I have a letter from Miss Linden.
- That's very nice. Where is she?

1544
01:52:18,600 --> 01:52:20,318
She's in St. Louis.

1545
01:52:20,720 --> 01:52:24,156
And here it comes. I gave you that medicine
to quiet your nerves.

1546
01:52:24,240 --> 01:52:26,913
Tony and the boys are with her.
They're on a concert tour.

1547
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:29,514
- They're on a what?
- Now I had their parents' consent...

1548
01:52:29,600 --> 01:52:31,875
- and they'll be back in time for school.
- But you...

1549
01:52:31,960 --> 01:52:34,030
Besides, travel's a great education.

1550
01:52:34,120 --> 01:52:37,112
If they make enough money,
it's gonna build you a new church.

1551
01:52:37,200 --> 01:52:40,636
Not much of one, maybe,
but something to go on with.

1552
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:45,356
Miss Linden sent you a cheque
with her love.

1553
01:52:50,360 --> 01:52:52,999
$3,500.

1554
01:52:53,080 --> 01:52:55,196
O'MALLEY: How's the pilot light
burning now?

1555
01:52:55,280 --> 01:52:57,032
It's burning brighter, Chuck.

1556
01:52:57,120 --> 01:52:59,270
It's a long road back, but we've started.

1557
01:52:59,360 --> 01:53:02,397
You know, I've a feeling
that St. Dominic's may rise again.

1558
01:53:02,480 --> 01:53:04,311
Sure it'll rise again.

1559
01:53:05,880 --> 01:53:09,839
- You know, I think I'll get up meself.
- You better stay there and get some rest.

1560
01:53:09,920 --> 01:53:13,037
- I feel better.
- No, you don't feel near that good.

1561
01:53:15,160 --> 01:53:18,596
Here now, boys. Go on home.

1562
01:53:18,680 --> 01:53:21,274
Your dinner's ready. Go on home.

1563
01:53:21,360 --> 01:53:23,476
BOY <i>1</i>: Bye, Father.
BOY 2: Goodbye, Father.

1564
01:53:25,080 --> 01:53:27,310
ALL: Bye, Father.

1565
01:53:32,840 --> 01:53:36,799
FITZGIBBON: Fine girl, Miss Linden.
Very thoughtful. Very generous.

1566
01:53:36,880 --> 01:53:39,348
Let's close this up. Keep the sawdust out.

1567
01:53:43,720 --> 01:53:46,280
That will lend beauty to the dedication.

1568
01:53:46,360 --> 01:53:48,715
And at Christmas,
you and the choir will be able to...

1569
01:53:48,800 --> 01:53:51,075
Father, I won't be here at Christmas.

1570
01:53:51,480 --> 01:53:55,871
I was with the Bishop this afternoon,
and he's transferring me to another parish.

1571
01:53:57,480 --> 01:53:58,799
[Exclaiming in disappointment]

1572
01:53:58,880 --> 01:54:00,598
You're leaving me.

1573
01:54:00,680 --> 01:54:03,399
It never occurred to me
that someday you might.

1574
01:54:04,080 --> 01:54:06,753
But, me boy,
what am I going to do without you?

1575
01:54:07,600 --> 01:54:11,593
- You didn't ask to?
- No. I asked to stay with you.

1576
01:54:12,120 --> 01:54:14,793
But the Bishop asked me to help him out,
and I...

1577
01:54:15,240 --> 01:54:18,869
- St. Dominic's. What's going to happen?
- Well, you'll be all right, Father.

1578
01:54:18,960 --> 01:54:22,430
I wish you could've heard some
of the things the Bishop said about you.

1579
01:54:22,520 --> 01:54:24,192
Says you're looking <i>1</i>0 years younger.

1580
01:54:24,280 --> 01:54:26,589
He has all the confidence
in the world in you.

1581
01:54:26,680 --> 01:54:28,989
Don't worry. You'll have a new assistant.

1582
01:54:29,080 --> 01:54:33,312
I want to wish you all the success
in the world, which I know you'll have.

1583
01:54:33,840 --> 01:54:35,910
Is it a parish of your own?

1584
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:38,275
Not exactly, Father.

1585
01:54:38,360 --> 01:54:41,875
You see this church, St. Charles, it's...

1586
01:54:42,360 --> 01:54:45,318
Well, the pastor's getting along in years
and things aren't...

1587
01:54:45,400 --> 01:54:47,470
You mean they're in trouble.

1588
01:54:47,560 --> 01:54:51,314
Yes. And I'm supposed to go in there
and try and help...

1589
01:54:51,400 --> 01:54:54,153
You mean without the old fella knowing.

1590
01:54:55,400 --> 01:54:59,109
Well, that's a difficult assignment.
But it'll work out.

1591
01:55:00,240 --> 01:55:03,198
You may have trouble
with the old man at first.

1592
01:55:03,280 --> 01:55:07,956
He may be running off to the Bishop every
few minutes, but don't let that bother you.

1593
01:55:09,200 --> 01:55:11,270
You'll bring him around
to your way of thinking.

1594
01:55:11,360 --> 01:55:12,395
[Bell ringing]

1595
01:55:12,480 --> 01:55:13,913
Well, there's dinner.

1596
01:55:14,560 --> 01:55:17,996
You know how to manage
these old fussbudgets.

1597
01:55:18,080 --> 01:55:21,277
Take him out on the golf course.
Bring him out in the fresh air.

1598
01:55:21,360 --> 01:55:26,275
- We'll get along. Just so he...
- He knows enough to come out of the rain.

1599
01:55:26,360 --> 01:55:28,920
That's it, Father. That's it exactly.

1600
01:55:32,920 --> 01:55:35,070
[Church bell chiming]

1601
01:55:37,440 --> 01:55:38,555
[Knock at door]

1602
01:55:38,640 --> 01:55:40,119
Come in, Tony.

1603
01:55:40,480 --> 01:55:44,075
- Hi, Father. So you're really leaving us?
- Yes, I've got my orders, Tony.

1604
01:55:44,160 --> 01:55:47,118
I guess when the Bishop says
you gotta go, you gotta go.

1605
01:55:47,200 --> 01:55:50,237
- That's right, Tony.
- Sometimes I think I don't like bishops.

1606
01:55:50,320 --> 01:55:52,072
Tony, bishops are like umpires.

1607
01:55:52,160 --> 01:55:54,390
You have to have them
to call the close decisions.

1608
01:55:54,480 --> 01:55:57,790
- Really?
- I got a little Christmas present here for you.

1609
01:55:57,880 --> 01:55:59,996
I want you to take my place with the choir.

1610
01:56:00,080 --> 01:56:01,957
From now on, you're in charge.

1611
01:56:02,040 --> 01:56:04,270
That's swell of you, Father.
It's a great present.

1612
01:56:04,360 --> 01:56:06,476
- I always had my eye on it.
- I thought you did.

1613
01:56:06,560 --> 01:56:09,313
When you gonna give
Father Fitzgibbon his surprise?

1614
01:56:09,400 --> 01:56:11,231
Not so loud. Later on in the church.

1615
01:56:11,320 --> 01:56:14,995
- Those boys haven't told anybody?
- Not a word. If they did, I'd kick the...

1616
01:56:15,080 --> 01:56:17,913
I mean, I'd be disappointed in them.
I guess I'll get going.

1617
01:56:18,000 --> 01:56:21,231
I know you wanted to tell me
about taking your place with the gang...

1618
01:56:21,320 --> 01:56:24,517
but I'll make it easy for you.
I'll be everything you want me to be.

1619
01:56:24,600 --> 01:56:26,397
Just as if you were here checking on me.

1620
01:56:26,480 --> 01:56:29,233
If you don't, I'm gonna drop you
like you was a hot potato.

1621
01:56:29,320 --> 01:56:32,517
- It's a deal. Good luck to you.
- Good luck to you. So long.

1622
01:56:41,800 --> 01:56:44,189
[Music box playing Irish lullaby]

1623
01:57:04,560 --> 01:57:06,391
Pretty near Christmas.

1624
01:57:32,080 --> 01:57:36,710
I'm sure that the way to say what I'd like
to say will occur to me after you've gone.

1625
01:57:38,840 --> 01:57:41,559
We're separated by many years,
Father O'Malley...

1626
01:57:41,640 --> 01:57:46,430
which could be the reason why we haven't
seen eye to eye in many instances.

1627
01:57:47,440 --> 01:57:51,319
But though we've had many differences,
we never differed in fundamentals.

1628
01:57:51,680 --> 01:57:55,309
- It was only in method.
- But never in our hearts.

1629
01:58:04,400 --> 01:58:06,231
- Good stuff, huh?
- Yes.

1630
01:58:07,360 --> 01:58:09,032
- Goodbye, Ted.
- Goodbye, Father.

1631
01:58:09,120 --> 01:58:11,839
Bye, Carol. Right man did come along?

1632
01:58:11,920 --> 01:58:13,911
Yes, but not past our house.

1633
01:58:14,600 --> 01:58:15,919
Stubborn?

1634
01:58:16,160 --> 01:58:18,355
- Goodbye, Mr. Haines.
- Father.

1635
01:58:20,640 --> 01:58:22,437
Pardon me, Mr. Haines.

1636
01:58:22,520 --> 01:58:26,229
I've just left the Bishop.
He told me to report to Father Fitzgibbon.

1637
01:58:26,320 --> 01:58:28,754
I'm taking your place. I'm the new curate!

1638
01:58:30,000 --> 01:58:33,072
You've little time. They're waiting
at the church to say goodbye.

1639
01:58:33,160 --> 01:58:35,355
All right. I've been doing you
a lot of good here.

1640
01:58:35,440 --> 01:58:37,476
You're gonna have a new church
after the war.

1641
01:58:37,560 --> 01:58:39,198
Yes, but we didn't raise enough money.

1642
01:58:39,280 --> 01:58:42,511
Mr. Haines is gonna give us a mortgage
to take care of the difference.

1643
01:58:42,600 --> 01:58:46,354
He convinced me I have a heart.
It wouldn't be a church without a mortgage.

1644
01:58:46,440 --> 01:58:48,032
- That's right.
- He's a wonder.

1645
01:58:48,120 --> 01:58:50,076
I don't know what I'm going to do
without him.

1646
01:58:50,160 --> 01:58:52,754
Don't know who the Bishop
is going to send in his place...

1647
01:58:52,840 --> 01:58:54,990
- but whoever he is...
- Father.

1648
01:59:00,480 --> 01:59:02,869
Congratulations to you, Father.

1649
01:59:03,400 --> 01:59:08,349
- The Bishop wouldn't do that to me again.
- Yes, he's done it.

1650
01:59:09,040 --> 01:59:12,032
Mr. Haines. Nice of you to give
that mortgage to the church.

1651
01:59:12,120 --> 01:59:13,235
HAINES: Not at all.

1652
01:59:13,320 --> 01:59:15,470
Can't tell you how much we appreciate it.

1653
01:59:22,240 --> 01:59:23,719
As you know...

1654
01:59:24,520 --> 01:59:27,512
we're all going to miss Father O'Malley.

1655
01:59:30,120 --> 01:59:31,792
He was a fine man.

1656
01:59:34,080 --> 01:59:37,117
This is Father O'Malley,
the man who sent for you.

1657
01:59:37,200 --> 01:59:38,952
How do you do, Mrs. Fitzgibbon?

1658
01:59:39,040 --> 01:59:41,679
I've heard so much about you.
Now it's good to see you.

1659
01:59:41,760 --> 01:59:45,878
FITZGIBBON: I think you'll agree that
we're all a little better for having known him.

1660
01:59:45,960 --> 01:59:48,349
He was always thinking of others.

1661
01:59:48,840 --> 01:59:51,593
And that, you know,
can make life very beautiful.

1662
01:59:51,680 --> 01:59:55,468
Believe me, it's what we do for others that...

1663
01:59:55,600 --> 01:59:58,114
[Boys singing Irish lullaby]

1664
02:00:56,560 --> 02:00:58,994
[Singing continues]

1665
02:01:15,000 --> 02:01:17,389
[Dramatic instrumental music]

